You said:
i would like to design a website that can track card sets and sort them by rarity, card number, alphabetical, language. The core sets I would like to track are Weiss Schwarz, Pokemon, magic the gathering, Lorcana, and One Piece with flaxibility to add more later. I own the domain masteraset.com through cloud flare and would like to host it there
ChatGPT said:

Heres a practical blueprint for masteraset.com: a card-set tracker that can browse/search/track ownership and sort/filter by rarity, card #, alphabetical, language, starting with Weiss Schwarz, Pokmon, MTG, Lorcana, One Pieceand designed to add more games later.

What youre building (features that matter)

Public Catalog side (anyone can browse)

  • Game selector (Weiss / Pokmon / MTG / Lorcana / One Piece / + later)

  • Set pages (set name, release date optional, language(s), set symbol, total cards, variants)

  • Card list with fast controls:

    • Sort: Card #, Name AZ, Rarity, Language

    • Filters: rarity, language, color/type (game-specific), has variant, etc.

    • Search: name / number / artist (optional) / text (optional)

Personal Collection side (logged-in)

  • Track Owned qty (normal / foil / alt-art / signed / graded, etc.)

  • Quick actions: +1 / -1, want list, trade list

  • Progress: % complete by set, missing cards, missing by rarity

Admin / Import side (you or trusted users)

  • Import sets + cards in bulk (CSV/JSON)

  • Map per-game rarities and numbering rules

  • Add/maintain language printings

The key design decision: one flexible data model across games

Each game has different quirks (rarity systems, numbering, variants). The trick is:

  • Keep a core universal model (Game Set CardPrinting)

  • Add game-specific metadata via a flexible JSON field or side tables.

Suggested core objects

  • Game

    • id, name, slug

  • Set

    • id, game_id, name, code, release_date, default_language, total_cards (optional)

  • Card (canonical)

    • id, game_id, canonical_name

  • Printing (this is what users actually collect)

    • id, set_id, card_id

    • collector_number (string, because formats vary: 123/198, EN-045, etc.)

    • language (EN/JP/etc.)

    • rarity (string + normalized_rarity_rank)

    • variant (normal/foil/alt-art/etc.)

    • image_url (optional)

    • extra (JSON for per-game fields: color, type, cost, trait, etc.)

  • User

  • UserCollectionItem

    • user_id, printing_id

    • qty_normal, qty_foil, qty_alt, notes, want (bool)

This makes sort by card # / rarity / language consistent across all games.

Hosting on Cloudflare (fits your setup perfectly)

Since your domain is already on Cloudflare, the clean Cloudflare-native stack is:

Option A (my recommended MVP stack)

  • Frontend: Next.js (or Remix) deployed on Cloudflare Pages

  • Backend/API: Cloudflare Pages Functions or Cloudflare Workers

  • Database: Cloudflare D1 (SQLite) for relational data (sets/cards/collections)

  • Caching/fast search: Cloudflare KV (optional) for cached set lists or precomputed filters

  • Images: Cloudflare R2 (optional) if you host images yourself

Why this works:

  • Very low ops

  • Global edge performance

  • Easy to connect domain Pages project

Option B (if you want heavy search later)

  • Keep everything above, and add Typesense/Meilisearch elsewhere, or build a D1-backed search index.

  • For MVP, you can get far with:

    • good DB indexes

    • server-side filtering

    • cached pages

Data sources (important reality check)

A set tracker lives or dies by data import.

  • MTG: There are strong public data sources (Scryfall is commonly used for MTG card data).

  • Pokmon / Weiss / Lorcana / One Piece: availability varies; you may need a mix of:

    • official lists when available

    • community databases

    • manual import via CSV

    • user-contributed corrections

Recommendation for MVP: design your own import format and start with manual CSV imports for a few sets per game. Then automate per game later.

Also: be careful with card imagesmany sources have rules; safest is:

  • store image links from permitted sources, or

  • dont show images in MVP (text-only), then add images once sourcing is settled.

    • owned count per card printing

v2

  • Variants/foils/alt-arts expanded

UI layout (simple and clean)

Top navigation

  • Games

  • My Collection

  • Import (admin)

  • Account

Set page

  • Header: Set name, language toggle, stats (312 cards 12 rarities)

  • Filters row:

    • Rarity dropdown

Database indexes youll want (performance)

To keep filtering fast:

  • printing(set_id, rarity)

  • printing(set_id, language)

  • printing(set_id, collector_number)

  • printing(set_id, name_sort) (or join to card)

  • user_collection(user_id, printing_id)

Below is a concrete MVP spec + database/API blueprint you can hand to a dev (or we can iterate into actual code).

MVP product scope for masteraset.com

Must-have (v1)

Catalog

  • Game Set list Set page (cards)

  • Card list supports:

    • Sort: collector number, name AZ, rarity, language

    • Filters: rarity, language, variant

    • Search: name/number

Accounts

  • Login required for collection features

  • Public browsing is optional; easiest is catalog public, collection private

Collection tracking

  • Per printing (set + number + language + variant + rarity):

    • quantity owned

  • One-click +1 / -1

  • Set progress:

    • Owned printings / total printings

    • Missing list

  • Wantlist / trade list flags (super valuable even in v1)

Nice-to-have (v1.1)

  • Bulk add (multi-select + quantity)

  • CSV import for your own data (admin-only)

The key: treat a collectible you can own as a PRINTING

Different languages + variants are different printings of the same underlying card concept.

Example

  • Pokmon Charizard #199 (EN) rainbow one printing

  • Same card JP version another printing

  • Alternate art another printing

Database schema (Cloudflare D1 / SQLite)

This structure stays clean across all games and supports variants/quantities.

Core tables

  • games

  • sets

  • cards (canonical identity)

  • printings (collectible units)

  • users

  • user_items (your ownership + want/trade)

Suggested schema (SQL-ish)

sql
-- GAMES
CREATE TABLE games (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  name TEXT NOT NULL,
  slug TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE
);

-- SETS
CREATE TABLE sets (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  game_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  name TEXT NOT NULL,
  code TEXT,                  -- e.g., S20, SV01, OP-05 etc (optional)
  release_date TEXT,          -- ISO date string optional
  default_language TEXT,      -- e.g., EN
  FOREIGN KEY (game_id) REFERENCES games(id)
);
CREATE INDEX idx_sets_game ON sets(game_id);

-- CANONICAL CARD (concept)
CREATE TABLE cards (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  game_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  canonical_name TEXT NOT NULL,
  name_sort TEXT NOT NULL,    -- normalized for sorting
  FOREIGN KEY (game_id) REFERENCES games(id)
);
CREATE INDEX idx_cards_game ON cards(game_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_cards_name_sort ON cards(name_sort);

-- PRINTING (the actual collectible entry)
CREATE TABLE printings (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  set_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  card_id TEXT NOT NULL,

  collector_number TEXT NOT NULL,  -- string because formats vary
  language TEXT NOT NULL,          -- EN/JP/DE etc
  rarity TEXT NOT NULL,            -- e.g., SR, UR, Rare, etc
  rarity_rank INTEGER NOT NULL,    -- normalized for sorting across that game

  variant TEXT NOT NULL,           -- normal/foil/alt-art/etc
  variant_rank INTEGER NOT NULL,   -- for consistent sorting

  image_url TEXT,                  -- optional
  extra_json TEXT,                 -- JSON for game-specific fields

  UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, variant),
  FOREIGN KEY (set_id) REFERENCES sets(id),
  FOREIGN KEY (card_id) REFERENCES cards(id)
);

CREATE INDEX idx_printings_set ON printings(set_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_printings_set_number ON printings(set_id, collector_number);
CREATE INDEX idx_printings_set_rarity ON printings(set_id, rarity_rank);
CREATE INDEX idx_printings_set_lang ON printings(set_id, language);
CREATE INDEX idx_printings_set_variant ON printings(set_id, variant_rank);

-- USERS
CREATE TABLE users (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  email TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE,
  display_name TEXT,
  created_at TEXT NOT NULL
);

-- USER OWNERSHIP (quantities + flags)
CREATE TABLE user_items (
  user_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  printing_id TEXT NOT NULL,

  qty INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
  want INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,     -- 0/1
  for_trade INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,

  note TEXT,
  updated_at TEXT NOT NULL,

  PRIMARY KEY (user_id, printing_id),
  FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users(id),
  FOREIGN KEY (printing_id) REFERENCES printings(id)
);
CREATE INDEX idx_user_items_user ON user_items(user_id);

Why collector_number is TEXT: across games youll see EN-045, 045a, 199/198, etc.

Why rarity_rank & variant_rank: you can display raw rarity text (game-specific) but still sort consistently.

Normalizing rarities & variants (so sorting works)

Rarity mapping per game

Create a small config table (or code config) that maps game rarity strings to rank numbers.

Example (not final each game differs):

  • Common = 10

  • Uncommon = 20

  • Rare = 30

  • SR/UR = 40

  • Secret = 50

For Weiss, youd map things like: C, U, R, RR, RRR, SR, SSP, SP, etc.

Variant mapping

Start simple:

  • Normal = 10

  • Foil/Holo = 20

  • Alt-Art = 30

  • Serialized = 40

  • Promo = 50

You can expand later without breaking the model.

API routes (MVP)

Assuming Next.js + Cloudflare Pages Functions (or Workers):

Public catalog

  • GET /api/games

  • GET /api/games/:gameSlug/sets

  • GET /api/sets/:setId

  • GET /api/sets/:setId/printings?sort=number|name|rarity|language&rarity=...&language=...&variant=...&q=...

Auth

  • POST /api/auth/start (email magic link)

  • GET /api/auth/callback (verify token)

Collection

  • GET /api/me

  • GET /api/me/sets/:setId (collection progress + owned items for this set)

  • POST /api/me/items/:printingId body: { "delta": +1 } (or { qty: 3 })

  • POST /api/me/items/:printingId/flags body: { want: true, for_trade: false }

Admin import (lock behind admin role)

  • POST /api/admin/import/printings (CSV/JSON)

  • POST /api/admin/import/sets

Pages / UX wireframe (simple & strong)

  1. / Landing (search bar + Choose a game)

  2. /games/:gameSlug Set list (filter by language optional)

  3. /sets/:setId

    • controls: Sort + Filters + Search

    • table/grid of printings with:

      • collector_number, name, rarity, language, variant

      • owned qty control (+ / - / edit)

  4. /me dashboard

    • set completion list

  5. /login magic link flow

Cloudflare deployment (fits your domain)

Recommended stack:

  • Cloudflare Pages (Next.js)

  • Cloudflare D1 (DB)

  • Cloudflare Turnstile (anti-bot on login)

  • Optional: R2 for images later

Your domain is already on Cloudflare, so pointing masteraset.com to Pages is straightforward.

How collection quantities & variants should behave (important details)

Rules

  • Qty can be 0+.

  • If qty becomes 0, you can either keep the row (with 0) or delete it I recommend keeping it if want or for_trade is set.

  • The unit you track is printing_id (so variants are naturally separated).

UI controls

  • default: show 0 with a + button

  • if qty > 0 show - qty +

  • click qty opens quick edit: set exact number

How to run it (local + Cloudflare)

1) Install

bash
npm install

2) Create D1

bash
npx wrangler d1 create masteraset-db

Then paste the returned database_id into wrangler.toml:

toml
database_id = "REPLACE_WITH_YOUR_D1_DATABASE_ID"

3) Run migrations

Local:

bash
npm run db:migrate:local

Remote:

bash
npm run db:migrate:remote

4) Start dev server

bash
npm run dev

5) Seed sample data (dev only)

Open the site click Dev: Seed Sample Data (home page)
That gives you a demo Pokmon set with Normal + Holo variants to test collection quantities.

Enabling real magic-link emails (when youre ready)

Right now the code prints the magic link to logs (stub). To make it real:

  1. Pick an email provider (Resend is simplest)

  2. Add env vars in Cloudflare Pages:

  • RESEND_API_KEY

  • APP_URL = https://masteraset.com

  1. In src/app/api/auth/start/route.ts, replace the stub sendEmailMagicLink() with the Resend fetch example already commented in the file.

You said:
i am struggling completing step 4. Node.js is giving me errors
ChatGPT said:

Got it step 4 (npm install) failing is almost always a Node setup issue (wrong version, permissions, or PATH). Here are the fastest fixes that solve ~95% of cases, in order.

1) First: confirm Node + npm are actually installed and visible

In Terminal / Command Prompt, run:

bash
node -v
npm -v

What you want to see:

  • Node: v18.x or v20.x (either is fine)

  • npm: prints a version number

If you get command not found / not recognized

That means Node didnt install correctly or your PATH isnt set.

Quick fix

  • Mac: close Terminal completely and reopen it (or restart your Mac).

  • Windows: close Command Prompt/PowerShell and reopen (or restart).

Then try node -v again.

2) If Node version is too old (common)

If node -v shows v16 or earlier, npm install can break.

Fix: install Node LTS (18 or 20).
If you already installed Node from nodejs.org but its still old, you likely have two Node installs.

Best fix (Mac + Windows): use NVM (manages Node versions cleanly)

Mac (recommended)

Install NVM + Node 20:

bash
curl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.39.7/install.sh | bash

Close Terminal, reopen, then:

bash
nvm install 20
nvm use 20
node -v

Windows (recommended)

Install nvm-windows (search nvm windows github releases), then:

powershell
nvm install 20
nvm use 20
node -v

Then rerun:

bash
npm install

3) If you see permissions errors (EPERM / EACCES)

Mac/Linux symptoms:

  • EACCES: permission denied

  • permission errors writing to folders

Fix: do NOT use sudo. Instead reset npm permissions:

bash
mkdir -p ~/.npm-global
npm config set prefix '~/.npm-global'

Then add this to your shell profile:

For zsh (most Macs):

bash
echo 'export PATH=~/.npm-global/bin:$PATH' >> ~/.zshrc
source ~/.zshrc

Now retry:

bash
npm install

Windows symptoms:

  • EPERM: operation not permitted

  • antivirus blocks file creation

Fix:

  • Right-click Terminal Run as Administrator

  • Temporarily disable Controlled folder access (Windows Security) if enabled

  • Retry npm install

4) If the project folder name/path has weird characters

Sometimes unzipping into iCloud/OneDrive or a path with odd chars causes failures.

Fix:

  • Move the unzipped folder to something simple like:

    • Mac: ~/Desktop/masteraset

    • Windows: C:\masteraset
      Then run:

bash
cd /path/to/masteraset
npm install

5) Clean reset (safe start over for npm install)

From inside the project folder:

bash
rm -rf node_modules package-lock.json
npm cache clean --force
npm install

(Windows PowerShell equivalent)

powershell
rmdir /s /q node_modules
del package-lock.json
npm cache clean --force
npm install

  • Are you on Mac or Windows?

  • What do these print?

    bash
    node -v

You said:
i am getting a 404 not found error in the terminal when i try and open the site
ChatGPT said:

Got it a 404 in the terminal when you open http://127.0.0.1:8788 means Wrangler is running, but its not serving your Next.js routes (so it doesnt see your homepage /).

This is usually caused by one config line in this starter: output: "standalone" in next.config.js. That setting is great for some hosts, but it commonly breaks next-on-pages local serving and leads to exactly what youre seeing: GET / 404.

Lets fix it with super granular steps.

Fix the 404 (do this exactly)

1) Stop the Cloudflare dev server

Go to the Terminal window thats running pages:dev and press:

CTRL + C

2) Edit next.config.js

Open the project folder on your computer.

Find and open this file:

next.config.js

Youll see something like:

js
const nextConfig = {
  output: "standalone",
  experimental: {
    serverActions: { allowedOrigins: ["masteraset.com"] }
  }
};
export default nextConfig;

Change it to this (remove the output: "standalone", line)

js
/** @type {import('next').NextConfig} */
const nextConfig = {
  experimental: {
    serverActions: { allowedOrigins: ["masteraset.com"] }
  }
};
export default nextConfig;

Save the file.

3) Rebuild the Cloudflare version

Back in Terminal (inside your project folder), run:

bash
npm run pages:build

Wait until it finishes without errors.

4) Start the Cloudflare dev server again

Run:

bash
npm run pages:dev

It should print a local URL. Now open:

http://localhost:8788/

(Use localhost instead of 127.0.0.1.)

Quick sanity check (important)

Sometimes people see a single 404 log because the browser requests /favicon.ico. Thats harmless.

So tell me which of these youre seeing:

  1. In Chrome you see a page that says 404 Not Found (big message)
    OR

  2. The page loads normally, but the terminal shows a 404 for /favicon.ico

If its #2, youre actually fine.

If its #1, do the fix above and it should resolve it.

If you want, paste the exact terminal lines that appear when you load http://localhost:8788/ (just the 35 lines). Ill confirm instantly whether its the real / route or just favicon noise.

Why youre seeing a security warning

Windows sometimes blocks files that came from a downloaded zip. Well unblock the folder/file and then edit normally.

Step A Unblock the folder (fastest fix)

  2. Find the .zip you downloaded (the original zip file)

  3. Right-click the zip Properties

  4. At the bottom, if you see Security: This file came from another computer
    Check Unblock click Apply OK

  5. Now re-extract (unzip) the file again (right click Extract All)

This usually removes the Windows protected your PC warnings for files inside.

What the error means (plain English)

This is the most reliable way to run Cloudflare Pages dev locally.

  3. Paste this and press Enter:

Think of WSL like:

A Linux app that runs inside Windows

It does not:

  • Reinstall Windows

  • Change your boot process

  • Delete or move your files

  • Affect OneDrive, Chrome, games, or anything else

It just adds:

A small Linux environment you can open when you want (like opening Photoshop or Steam)

You can:

  • Close it

  • Never use it again

  • Or uninstall it later

Nothing breaks.

Why this is needed

Cloudflares dev tools were built for Linux & Mac.
On Windows, they rely on bash, which only exists in:

  • Linux

  • macOS

  • or WSL

Thats why you got:
spawn bash ENOENT

This is extremely common every Windows dev using Cloudflare Pages uses WSL.

Your options (you choose)

Option A Best (Recommended)

Install WSL (5 minutes)
You get:

  • Local dev works

  • Database works

  • You can test MasteraSet before publishing

Option B Skip local dev

We skip Pages Dev and push straight to Cloudflare Pages (Linux server).
This works, but:

  • You wont see it locally

  • Debugging is slower

Given how much work youre putting into this, Option A is far better.

If you say Yes, install WSL

Ill give you 3 commands, copy/paste style, that get you there safely.

If you say No
Ill give you the fastest Cloudflare deploy path instead.

ChatGPT said:

Thanks that screenshot is the key.

What went wrong (in plain English)

Your build failed because Next.js cant resolve imports that start with @/, like:

  • import { getEnv } from "@/lib/cloudflare";

That alias (@/) only works if your tsconfig.json defines it. Right now it doesnt, so the build stops with Module not found.

Well fix it by adding 2 lines to tsconfig.json, then rebuilding.

Fix it (very specific steps, one window, in Ubuntu)

Step 1 Open tsconfig.json for editing

In Ubuntu, make sure youre in the project folder (you already are), then type:

bash
nano tsconfig.json

Press Enter.

Step 2 Add the alias config

Inside the file, find:

json
"compilerOptions": {

Inside compilerOptions, add these two lines (anywhere inside that block is fine, I usually put them near the top):

json
"baseUrl": ".",
"paths": { "@/*": ["src/*"] },

So your compilerOptions will look like this (example):

json
"compilerOptions": {
  "baseUrl": ".",
  "paths": { "@/*": ["src/*"] },
  "target": "ES2022",
  ...
}

Step 3 Save and exit nano

  • Press CTRL + O (write out / save)

  • Press Enter (confirm)

  • Press CTRL + X (exit)

Step 4 Rebuild

Now run:

bash
npm run pages:build

Tell me what happens

If it succeeds, great well run the dev server next.

If it fails, paste the last ~10 lines of the error and Ill guide the next fix.

This usually happens when tsconfig.json got accidentally corrupted most commonly:

bash

    "resolveJsonModule": true,
    "isolatedModules": true,
    "jsx": "preserve",
    "incremental": true,

    "types": ["@cloudflare/workers-types"]
  },
  "include": ["next-env.d.ts", "src/**/*.ts", "src/**/*.tsx"],
  "exclude": ["node_modules"]
}
EOF

That command overwrites tsconfig.json with the correct contents.

Great progress. Now were hitting a TypeScript typing error, not a Cloudflare/WSL error.

Whats happening

Cloudflare D1s .first() returns a value TypeScript treats as unknown, so when you do:

tsx
<h2>{game.name} Sets</h2>

TypeScript complains: unknown is not a valid ReactNode.

Fix: explicitly cast the DB result to a known type (or any for now).

Well do this one file at a time.

Step 1 Fix src/app/games/[slug]/page.tsx

In Ubuntu (in your Masteraset folder), run:

bash
nano src/app/games/[slug]/page.tsx

Find this line (or very close to it):

ts
const game = await env.DB.prepare("SELECT id, name FROM games WHERE slug = ?").bind(params.slug).first();

Replace it with this:

ts
const game = (await env.DB
  .prepare("SELECT id, name FROM games WHERE slug = ?")
  .bind(params.slug)
  .first()) as any;

Now save and exit:

  • Enter

You said:
why is my run time set to 2024?
ChatGPT said:

Thats a really good question and it actually means your setup is working correctly.

Short version:

Your computer is using the latest Cloudflare Workers engine it has, and right now that engine supports features up to August 2024.

It is not your Windows date.
It is not your project version.
It is not something you did wrong.

What the date actually means

Cloudflare Workers runs on a runtime that evolves over time (like a browser engine).
Each compatibility date is basically:

Pretend its this version of the Cloudflare Workers engine.

Your log said:

Latest supported date: 2024-08-06
You requested: 2025-01-01
Falling back to 2024-08-06

So Cloudflare just said:

I dont support 2025 features yet, so Im using the newest one I do support.

Thats normal.

When Cloudflare updates Wrangler, that date will move forward.

Why we changed it

We changed your config to:

ini
compatibility_date = "2024-08-06"

So:

  • Cloudflare stops warning

  • Node.js compatibility works

  • Your site runs correctly

Nothing about your app is stuck in 2024.
It just tells Cloudflare which runtime features to enable.

Think of it like this

Its the same idea as:

Run this website using Chrome version August 2024.

Youre not using an old OS youre using the most stable supported Workers engine.

Next step

Now that Node compatibility is set, your site should load cleanly.

Open:
http://localhost:8788

  • Or an error message?

Why this works

Your build output is trying to import an internal shim module (__next-on-pages-dist__/functions/async_hooks). Its missing, so it crashes. By creating that file and re-exporting from node:async_hooks (enabled by nodejs_compat), the imports resolve and the runtime stops 500ing.

You did everything right this is now down to how the generated build files are importing async_hooks.

Right now your generated function file is trying to import exactly:

arduino
"__next-on-pages-dist__/functions/async_hooks"

Cloudflares module resolver does not reliably auto-resolve extensionless imports, even if the file exists. The clean fix is:

  1. create async_hooks.js

  2. patch the generated imports to point to async_hooks.js

Well do this with copy/paste commands.

Step 1 Stop the server

In the Ubuntu window running wrangler, press:

CTRL + C

Step 2 Create the shim files in the correct folder

Run this in Ubuntu:

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset

mkdir -p __next-on-pages-dist__/functions
mkdir -p __next-on-pages-dist__/functions/admin

cat > __next-on-pages-dist__/functions/async_hooks.js << 'EOF'
export * from "node:async_hooks";
export { AsyncLocalStorage } from "node:async_hooks";
EOF

cat > __next-on-pages-dist__/functions/admin/async_hooks.js << 'EOF'
export * from "node:async_hooks";
export { AsyncLocalStorage } from "node:async_hooks";
EOF

Step 3 Patch the generated imports to include .js

Run:

bash
# Patch any function files that import the extensionless async_hooks path
grep -R "__next-on-pages-dist__/functions/async_hooks" -n __next-on-pages-dist__/functions | head -n 20

# Replace imports to point to async_hooks.js
find __next-on-pages-dist__/functions -type f -name "*.js" -print0 \
  | xargs -0 sed -i 's#__next-on-pages-dist__/functions/async_hooks#__next-on-pages-dist__/functions/async_hooks.js#g'

(That updates the generated games.func.js and any others using the same import.)

Step 4 Start the server again

Run:

bash
npx wrangler pages dev .vercel/output/static

When it says ready, open:

http://localhost:8788/games

Copy/paste the new error line from the Ubuntu server window. If it complains about another missing Node shim (like buffer, stream, etc.), well add it the same way.

This specific patch is the reliable way to get past the async_hooks import problem on Windows+WSL with next-on-pages.

ChatGPT said:

Youre very close, and the output you pasted reveals the real issue.

Key discovery (from your grep)

Inside the WORKER copy of games.func.js, it is importing:

js
import * as X_ from "async_hooks";

That is not importing __next-on-pages-dist__/functions/async_hooks anymore.

On Cloudflare Workers, even with nodejs_compat, the safe import is:

js
import * as X_ from "node:async_hooks";

So the fix is: patch the generated worker functions to use node:async_hooks (and well do it in one command).

Well do this in your single Ubuntu window.

Step 1 Stop the server

Press CTRL + C

Step 2 Patch ALL generated worker functions to use node:async_hooks

Copy/paste this exactly:

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset

# Replace bare async_hooks import with node:async_hooks in the generated worker output
find .vercel/output/static/_worker.js/__next-on-pages-dist__/functions -type f -name "*.js" -print0 \
  | xargs -0 sed -i 's#from"async_hooks"#from"node:async_hooks"#g'

Now confirm it worked for the games function:

bash
grep -n 'from"node:async_hooks"' .vercel/output/static/_worker.js/__next-on-pages-dist__/functions/games.func.js | head -n 5

You should see a line showing node:async_hooks.

Step 3 Start the server again with node compat enabled

bash
npx wrangler pages dev .vercel/output/static --compatibility-date=2024-08-06 --compatibility-flags=nodejs_compat

Step 4 Test

Open in Chrome:

  • http://localhost:8788/games

If it still errors

Paste the next error line from Wrangler. If it complains about another Node builtin (like buffer, stream, etc.), well patch those the same way (usually from"buffer" from"node:buffer").

Run Step 2 + Step 4 and tell me whether /games loads.

You said:
yes i see this. I want to make sure for the card number data field that we will be able to capture the correct card number. this is one fail point i see on many other tracking sites. You can sort alphabetically and other ways but not in the set specific card order.
ChatGPT said:

100% agree card number is where a lot of trackers quietly fail, because set order is not the same as alphabetical and card numbers arent truly numbers in many games.

The way to make this rock-solid is:

The rule: store the exact printed number, plus a sortable order key

For every printing, we should store:

  1. collector_number_raw (string)

  • Exactly whats on the card: 001/198, TG12/TG30, OP01-001, P-001, EN-1/204, etc.

  1. collector_order_key (string or integer)

  • A normalized value we compute so sorting is perfect for that specific set/game.

  1. set_order_override (optional)

  • A manual this card is position 153 in the set override for edge cases, promos, errors, alternate arts that dont follow normal patterns.

Then Sort by set order becomes:

  • If set_order_override exists use that

  • Else use collector_order_key

  • Else fallback to collector_number_raw (so its never blank)

This guarantees you can always get correct set order.

Why collector_number_raw alone is not enough

Different games do stuff like:

  • Pokmon: 001/198, TG12/TG30, SVP 123, SWSH045, secrets like 201/198

  • MTG: 123, 123a, 123, set-dependent quirks, multi-language collector numbers

  • One Piece: OP01-001, ST01-001, promos like P-001

  • Lorcana: often 1/204 plus set/ink/variant differences

  • Weiss Schwarz: not purely numeric; often code-based IDs (set code + number) where set-specific order can be non-trivial

If you sort those as strings, you get garbage ordering (100 before 20, promos mixed wrong, TG subsets in the wrong place, etc.).

How we implement it in your database (small change, big payoff)

Right now you have collector_number on printings. Id adjust printings to:

  • collector_number_raw (string) rename current collector_number to this

  • collector_order_key (string) computed normalization used for sorting

  • set_order_override (integer nullable) optional manual absolute position

Then your sort query becomes:

sql
ORDER BY
  COALESCE(set_order_override, NULL) ASC,
  collector_order_key ASC,
  collector_number_raw ASC,
  name_sort ASC

(We can implement the override as very first sort key by using a CASE expression if needed, but the concept stands.)

How we compute collector_order_key (game-aware)

Well build a per-game parser that generates an order key that sorts correctly:

Pokmon (examples)

  • 001/198 key like BASE|000001

  • 201/198 (secret) BASE|000201 (so it naturally falls after 198)

  • TG12/TG30 TG|000012

  • SVP 123 SVP|000123

This keeps subsets grouped and ordered correctly.

One Piece

  • OP01-001 OP01|000001

  • ST01-001 ST01|000001

  • P-001 PROMO|000001 (and promos can be placed at end or in their own tab depending on your preference)

MTG

  • 123 000123

  • 123a 000123|A

  • 123 000123|STAR
    We preserve suffixes so variants stay adjacent and stable.

Lorcana

  • 1/204 000001

  • Enchanted/alternate numbering subset key like ENCH|000xxx if theyre numbered outside base

Weiss Schwarz

Well treat their printed ID as raw and also allow set-specific ordering rules:

  • Many Weiss cards are best ordered by the numeric portion, but rarity/parallel codes can interfere.

  • If a set has an official checklist order that differs from numeric order, thats where set_order_override saves you.

The never fail safety net

Even with parsers, there will always be weird edge cases (misprints, regional promos, EX cards, reprints, etc.).

Thats why I strongly recommend keeping an override mechanism:

  • Admin UI: Set order position

  • You can fix any problematic card in 5 seconds without waiting for a code update

This is the difference between pretty good tracker and actually correct tracker.

ChatGPT said:

Got it you want true checklist order, not close enough. And you want it to stay correct even when companies invent new numbering formats.

The way to future-proof this is to separate:

  1. whats printed on the card (never lose fidelity)

  2. how we sort it (a consistent, configurable priority system)

Below is the model that handles both Pokmon 130/094 and Weiss E38 with multiple rarities/variants.

1) Store the printed ID exactly, but also store parsed pieces

For every printing (a specific card in a specific set, language, rarity, variant), store:

A. Printed fields (never change)

  • set_code: PFL (your example)

  • language: EN

  • collector_number_raw: 130/094 (Pokmon) or E38 (Weiss)

  • rarity_code: C, U, R, RR, RRR, SR, etc. (whatever the game uses)

  • variant: Normal, Holo, Foil, Alt Art, SP, SSP, etc.

B. Parsed fields (for sorting; can be recalculated later)

  • num_prefix (string, nullable): e.g. TG, SVP, P-, OP01- (whatever appears before the digits)

  • num_value (integer, nullable): the numeric part (e.g. 130, 38)

  • num_suffix (string, nullable): letters/symbols (e.g. a, )

  • num_total (integer, nullable): from 130/094 94 (useful for display, not required for sorting)

  • subset_code (string, nullable): for Pokmon subsets like TG, AR, SAR etc (sometimes this is the prefix, sometimes separate depending on set)

This lets you display exactly what collectors expect while keeping sorting deterministic.

2) Build a single set order rule that always works

Your Weiss requirement is key:

All variations of E38 should appear together, ordered by rarity priority, before E39.

That means the sort keys must be ordered like this:

Sort order inside a selected set

  1. num_value (E38 38)

  2. num_suffix / prefix (only if needed)

  3. rarity_rank (Common before Uncommon before Rare )

  4. variant_rank (Normal before Foil before Alt Art before SP/SSP )

  5. name_sort as a final tie-breaker

So the set page ordering becomes:

  • E38 Common

  • E38 Uncommon

  • E38 Rare

  • E38 RR

  • E38 RRR

  • then move to E39

Same for Pokmon:

  • 094/094 base ends

  • then 095/094, 096/094, secret cards continue naturally because we sort by num_value.

3) Rarity priority must be data-driven per game (future-proof)

Companies will always change naming. So we dont hardcode RRR > RR in code.

Instead we add a table:

rarity_priority

  • game_id

  • rarity_code (e.g. C, U, R, RR, RRR, SR, SP, SSP)

  • rarity_rank (integer; lower = earlier in list)

  • optional: display_name

Then you can define Weiss ranks exactly how you want, and tweak later without a code change.

Same for variant ordering:

variant_priority

  • game_id

  • variant (Normal, Foil, Alt Art, SP, SSP, etc.)

  • variant_rank

This is how we future-proof new identifiers: if a new rarity shows up, you add one row with its rank.

4) Handle Set code first the way you described

You said:

Set is classified as PFL > EN 130/094

Thats perfect. The user flow is: pick a set show all printings in that set.

So the set page query always filters by set_id first. Once youre inside that set, set_code isnt part of sorting anymore (because youre already scoped).

But for global searches (across all sets), you sort like:

  • game

  • set_code

  • language

  • num_value

  • rarity_rank

  • variant_rank

5) Parsing strategy (how we survive weird formats)

We keep parsing pluggable and simple:

Universal parsing (works for most games)

  • Extract digits as num_value

  • Anything before digits num_prefix

  • Anything after digits num_suffix

  • If raw contains / parse right side as num_total

Examples:

  • 130/094 num_value=130, num_total=94

  • E38 prefix=E, num_value=38

  • OP01-001 prefix=OP01-, num_value=1

  • 123a num_value=123, suffix=a

Future-proof override (for edge cases)

Add optional columns:

  • sort_group (string) and/or

  • set_order_override (integer)

If a particular set has a totally bizarre ordering rule, you can pin it without rewriting the parser.

6) What we should change in your current app (minimum changes, maximum benefit)

Right now you already have collector_number, rarity_rank, variant_rank. Great start.

I recommend we add these to printings:

  • collector_number_raw (rename existing collector_number to this)

  • num_prefix TEXT

  • num_value INTEGER

  • num_suffix TEXT

  • num_total INTEGER NULL

  • set_order_override INTEGER NULL

Then update the set page sorting to:

  1. COALESCE(set_order_override, 999999999) (so overrides come first if present)

  2. num_value

  3. num_prefix

  4. num_suffix

  5. rarity_rank

  6. variant_rank

This exactly matches your Weiss E38 grouped with priority requirement.

1) Add Promo placement as a first-class sorting rule

You want:

  • Promos last unless they use base numbering that fits within the set.

Future-proof way to do that:

Add two fields on each printing

  • is_promo (boolean)

  • promo_sort_bucket (integer) derived, but we can store it

Rules:

  • If is_promo = 1 and the printed number clearly belongs to the base numbering system promo_sort_bucket = 0 (treat like normal)

  • If is_promo = 1 and its a promo-style identifier (prefix like P-, PR, SVP, WSP, etc.) promo_sort_bucket = 1 (force to end)

Then your set checklist ORDER BY starts with:

  1. promo_sort_bucket (0 first, 1 last)

  2. num_value

  3. num_prefix

  4. num_suffix

  5. rarity_rank

  6. variant_rank

That gives you exactly what you described.

Why not just is_promo?
Because some promos do fit the normal numbering and you want them to behave normally.

3) Promo detection rules (practical defaults)

For promo routing, we can keep it simple and correct most of the time:

Mark as promo if any are true:

  • set is explicitly a promo set (if you track promo sets separately)

  • number prefix indicates promo: P-, PR, PROMO, SVP, SWSH, WSP (Weiss promos), etc.

  • the printing is flagged is_promo by importer/manual edit

Then determine whether it fits base numbering:

  • If num_value is within base range and num_prefix matches the sets normal prefix (or is blank), then promo_sort_bucket=0

  • Otherwise promo_sort_bucket=1 (force last)

If you dont know the base range (like Pokmons 094), thats okay: we can store base_total on the set (optional) and use it when available. But even without it, promo-ish prefixes go last solves 90% of the pain.

Your rule, translated into a future-proof sorter

When a user is inside a set:

  1. If a card has a real base number (like E38, 130/094, OP01-001):

  • It should appear in the normal numeric flow.

  • Within that same number, chase versions (SP/SSP/SEC/etc.) should appear after the lower rarities (as you said: last in that priority).

  1. If a card does NOT follow the numbering system (no usable number, or a promo-style identifier):

  • It should be forced to the end of the checklist.

That means we need one additional sort bucket before we sort numerically.

The sorting model that implements this cleanly

Fields on each printing (what we store)

  • collector_number_raw (string) exactly whats printed

  • num_prefix (string|null) e.g., E, OP01-, TG, P-

  • num_value (int|null) e.g., 38, 130, 1

  • num_suffix (string|null)

  • rarity_code (string) C, U, RR, SP, SEC, etc.

  • rarity_rank (int) per game mapping

  • variant_rank (int)

Two derived booleans/buckets (this is the magic)

  • numbered_bucket (int)

    • 0 = normal numbered card (participates in set order)

    • 1 = numbered promo that still fits base numbering (optional if you want)

    • 2 = unnumbered / nonconforming (forced to end)

  • promo_bucket (int)

    • 0 = normal

    • 1 = promo (tends to end unless it fits)

You can implement with just one bucket if you want; I like two because promos and weird numbering are separate problems.

The actual ORDER BY (set checklist)

When viewing a set, sort like:

  1. numbered_bucket (0 first, 2 last)

  2. promo_bucket (0 first, 1 last unless you decide promos should always be last regardless)

  3. num_value ASC

  4. num_prefix ASC

  5. num_suffix ASC

  6. rarity_rank ASC this gives your E38 C before E38 RR before E38 SP

  7. variant_rank ASC

  8. name_sort ASC (final tie-break)

This guarantees:

  • All E38s stay together

  • E38 chase versions appear last within E38

  • Anything without a real E-number goes to the end

How we decide has base numbering

We do it with a per-game parser + a per-set numbering profile.

For Weiss

  • If collector_number_raw matches something like ^[A-Z]+(\d+)$ (e.g., E38) num_prefix='E', num_value=38, numbered_bucket=0

  • If its something like PR, PXX, event promo codes, etc. and we cant extract a stable number num_value=null, numbered_bucket=2 (goes to end)

For Pokmon

  • 130/094 num_value=130, num_total=94, numbered_bucket=0 (so secrets naturally appear after 94)

  • Promo-style ones (e.g., SVP 123) you can choose:

    • If its a promo set, its its own set anyway

    • If it appears inside a normal set page, promo_bucket=1 and usually numbered_bucket=2 unless you explicitly want it in-line

-- Add fields needed for correct set-order sorting (Weiss/Pokemon/etc.)

ALTER TABLE printings ADD COLUMN num_total INTEGER;

-- Buckets:
-- numbered_bucket: 0 = normal numbered, 2 = nonconforming/unnumbered (send to end)
ALTER TABLE printings ADD COLUMN numbered_bucket INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0;

-- promo_bucket: 0 = normal, 1 = promo (send later than normal)
ALTER TABLE printings ADD COLUMN promo_bucket INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0;

-- Optional manual override (absolute position in checklist if ever needed)
ALTER TABLE printings ADD COLUMN set_order_override INTEGER;

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set_order
ON printings(set_id, numbered_bucket, promo_bucket, num_value, rarity_rank, variant_rank);
EOF

npm run db:migrate:local

3) Update the set page to sort in true set order

Well change only the Card # sort to:

  • numbered cards first

  • promos/nonconforming last

  • numeric order (E38 before E39)

  • rarity priority inside the same number

Edit this file:

src/app/sets/[setId]/page.tsx

Find the orderBy(sort) function and replace it with this version (copy/paste the whole function):

ts
function orderBy(sort: SortKey) {
  // "Set order" (number) should be: numbered cards first, then promos/nonconforming,
  // and within a number, apply rarity_rank + variant_rank.
  const setOrder =
    "COALESCE(p.set_order_override, 999999999) ASC, " +
    "p.numbered_bucket ASC, " +
    "p.promo_bucket ASC, " +
    "COALESCE(p.num_value, 999999999) ASC, " +
    "COALESCE(p.num_prefix, '') ASC, " +
    "COALESCE(p.num_suffix, '') ASC, " +
    "p.rarity_rank ASC, " +
    "p.variant_rank ASC, " +
    "p.collector_number ASC";

  switch (sort) {
    case "name": return "c.name_sort ASC";
    case "rarity": return "p.rarity_rank ASC, c.name_sort ASC";
    case "language": return "p.language ASC, " + setOrder;
    case "variant": return "p.variant_rank ASC, " + setOrder;
    case "number":
    default: return setOrder;
  }
}

Save the file.

Why youre only seeing 2x E38 (C + SP)

Step B Fix the UI if its deduping (likely)

Open this file again:

src/app/sets/[setId]/page.tsx

Press CTRL+F and search for any of these:

  • DISTINCT

  • GROUP BY

  • cards c

  • FROM cards

  • SELECT c.

The goal: the results should be based on printings p (each printing is a row), not collapsed to one row per card.

What the query should conceptually look like

It should be something like:

sql
SELECT
  p.id as printing_id,
  p.collector_number,
  p.rarity,
  p.rarity_rank,
  p.language,
  p.variant,
  p.variant_rank,
  c.canonical_name
FROM printings p
JOIN cards c ON c.id = p.card_id
WHERE p.set_id = ?
ORDER BY ...

If your query has GROUP BY c.id or SELECT DISTINCT c.id, thats exactly why youre only seeing one (or two) E38 rows.

You said:
i am only seeing C and SP and i do see Distinct in the code as well as join cards c
ChatGPT said:

Great catch both things you said are important, and they explain exactly why you only see C + SP:

Why only C and SP exist in the DB

Your database schema has this UNIQUE constraint on printings (from migrations/0001_init.sql):

UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, variant)

So when we tried to insert E38 multiple times, anything that shared the same:

  • set_id = s_5hy_we43

  • collector_number = E38

  • language = JP

  • variant = Normal (or Foil)

got ignored.

That means:

  • E38 C Normal inserted

  • E38 U Normal got blocked (same set+number+language+variant as C Normal)

  • E38 RR Normal blocked

  • E38 SP Foil inserted (different variant)

  • E38 SEC Foil blocked (same Foil variant)

So the schema must be updated to allow multiple rarities per number. Thats required for Weiss to work the way you want.

Fix: Change the UNIQUE constraint to include rarity (and variant)

We want printings to be unique per:

(set_id, collector_number, language, rarity, variant)

That allows:

  • E38 C Normal

  • E38 U Normal

  • E38 RR Normal

  • E38 SP Foil

  • E38 SEC Foil

all to coexist.

SQLite cant ALTER TABLE DROP CONSTRAINT easily, so we do the safe migration: create a new table, copy, swap.

Step 1 Stop the server

If Wrangler is running: CTRL + C

Step 2 Add a migration to rebuild printings with correct uniqueness

Copy/paste this exactly:

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset

cat > migrations/0003_printings_unique_fix.sql << 'EOF'
-- Rebuild printings table to fix UNIQUE constraint.
-- Old: UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, variant)
-- New: UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, rarity, variant)

PRAGMA foreign_keys=OFF;

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS printings_new (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  set_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  card_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  collector_number TEXT NOT NULL,
  language TEXT NOT NULL,
  rarity TEXT NOT NULL,
  rarity_rank INTEGER NOT NULL,
  variant TEXT NOT NULL,
  variant_rank INTEGER NOT NULL,
  image_url TEXT,
  extra_json TEXT,

  -- Set order fields (from your 0002 migration)
  num_prefix TEXT,
  num_value INTEGER,
  num_suffix TEXT,
  num_total INTEGER,
  numbered_bucket INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
  promo_bucket INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
  set_order_override INTEGER,

  UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, rarity, variant),
  FOREIGN KEY (set_id) REFERENCES sets(id),
  FOREIGN KEY (card_id) REFERENCES cards(id)
);

INSERT INTO printings_new (
  id, set_id, card_id, collector_number, language, rarity, rarity_rank,
  variant, variant_rank, image_url, extra_json,
  num_prefix, num_value, num_suffix, num_total, numbered_bucket, promo_bucket, set_order_override
)
SELECT
  id, set_id, card_id, collector_number, language, rarity, rarity_rank,
  variant, variant_rank, image_url, extra_json,
  num_prefix, num_value, num_suffix, num_total, numbered_bucket, promo_bucket, set_order_override
FROM printings;

DROP TABLE printings;

ALTER TABLE printings_new RENAME TO printings;

-- Recreate indexes (including your new set-order index)
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set ON printings(set_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set_number ON printings(set_id, collector_number);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set_rarity ON printings(set_id, rarity_rank);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set_lang ON printings(set_id, language);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set_variant ON printings(set_id, variant_rank);

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set_order
ON printings(set_id, numbered_bucket, promo_bucket, num_value, rarity_rank, variant_rank);

PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON;
EOF

Now apply migrations:

bash
npm run db:migrate:local

Change the uniqueness to include rarity:

This is essential for Weiss and also helps other games with multiple versions by rarity that share the same printed number.

  • num_value ASC

Use DISTINCT and order by min rank:

WHERE set_id = ?

That keeps the dropdown clean and still correctly ordered.

Refinement Plan (Weiss-ready)

Step 1 Fix the printings uniqueness rule (required for Weiss)

We need to allow multiple rarities per same number. The correct uniqueness is:

UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, rarity, variant)

1B) Add a migration that rebuilds the printings table

Copy/paste exactly:

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset

cat > migrations/0003_printings_unique_fix.sql << 'EOF'
-- Fix UNIQUE constraint so Weiss can have multiple rarities for the same card number
-- Old: UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, variant)
-- New: UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, rarity, variant)

PRAGMA foreign_keys=OFF;

CREATE TABLE printings_new (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  set_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  card_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  collector_number TEXT NOT NULL,
  language TEXT NOT NULL,
  rarity TEXT NOT NULL,
  rarity_rank INTEGER NOT NULL,
  variant TEXT NOT NULL,
  variant_rank INTEGER NOT NULL,
  image_url TEXT,
  extra_json TEXT,

  -- Set-order fields added previously
  num_prefix TEXT,
  num_value INTEGER,
  num_suffix TEXT,
  num_total INTEGER,
  numbered_bucket INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
  promo_bucket INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
  set_order_override INTEGER,

  UNIQUE(set_id, collector_number, language, rarity, variant),
  FOREIGN KEY (set_id) REFERENCES sets(id),
  FOREIGN KEY (card_id) REFERENCES cards(id)
);

INSERT INTO printings_new (
  id, set_id, card_id, collector_number, language, rarity, rarity_rank,
  variant, variant_rank, image_url, extra_json,
  num_prefix, num_value, num_suffix, num_total, numbered_bucket, promo_bucket, set_order_override
)
SELECT
  id, set_id, card_id, collector_number, language, rarity, rarity_rank,
  variant, variant_rank, image_url, extra_json,
  num_prefix, num_value, num_suffix, num_total, numbered_bucket, promo_bucket, set_order_override
FROM printings;

DROP TABLE printings;
ALTER TABLE printings_new RENAME TO printings;

-- Indexes
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set ON printings(set_id);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_printings_set_order
ON printings(set_id, numbered_bucket, promo_bucket, num_value, rarity_rank, variant_rank);

PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON;
EOF

Step 4 Fix Weiss Schwarz numbering so E38 variants stay together

Right now your ordering is:

swift
num_value  prefix  suffix  rarity_rank  variant_rank

Thats good but Weiss Schwarz breaks this because:

powershell
E38
E38U
E38R
E38RR
E38SP

All share the same number (38) but differ by suffix + rarity.

We need to introduce a Weiss-specific card-number tier that sits between number and rarity.

4.1 Add a number_variant_rank to printings

In your DB, each printing already has:

  • num_value

  • num_prefix

  • num_suffix

  • rarity

  • rarity_rank

We need to add one more derived field:

number_variant_rank

For Weiss, this means:

Collector #number_variant_rank
E380
E38U1
E38R2
E38RR3
E38RRR4
E38SP5
E38SEC6

This ensures all E38s stay together, and within them, rarity order applies.

4.2 Create the Weiss variant priority map

We will encode this once and reuse it for all Weiss sets:

ts
const WEISS_SUFFIX_PRIORITY: Record<string, number> = {
  "": 0,      // Base
  "U": 1,
  "R": 2,
  "RR": 3,
  "RRR": 4,
  "XR": 5,
  "SEC": 6,
  "SP": 7,
  "AGR": 8,
  "PR": 99    // promos always last
};

Anything unknown gets default 50.

4.3 Add this logic when importing cards

Wherever you are inserting printings (your seed script or import pipeline), compute:

ts
const suffix = parsed.num_suffix ?? "";

const numberVariantRank =
  WEISS_SUFFIX_PRIORITY[suffix] ?? 50;

And store it:

pgsql
number_variant_rank INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0

4.4 Update the ORDER BY to use it

In your orderBy() function, change this line:

ts
"COALESCE(p.num_suffix, '') ASC, " +
"p.rarity_rank ASC, "

to:

ts
"p.number_variant_rank ASC, " +
"p.rarity_rank ASC, "

Your new setOrder becomes:

ts
const setOrder =
  "COALESCE(p.set_order_override, 999999999) ASC, " +
  "p.numbered_bucket ASC, " +
  "p.promo_bucket ASC, " +
  "COALESCE(p.num_value, 999999999) ASC, " +
  "COALESCE(p.num_prefix, '') ASC, " +
  "p.number_variant_rank ASC, " +
  "p.rarity_rank ASC, " +
  "p.variant_rank ASC, " +
  "p.collector_number ASC";

Next milestone

Auto-parse Weiss numbers + auto-bucket promos/nonconforming

What this will do

When you import/add a Weiss printing with a collector number like:

  • E38 prefix E, value 38, numbered_bucket 0, promo_bucket 0

  • E38 with rarity PR (or collector_number PR) numbered_bucket 2, promo_bucket 1 (goes to end)

  • Anything we cant parse into a stable number numbered_bucket 2 (goes to end)

And it will apply to every set (including 5HY/WE43).

Step 1 Add a Weiss number parser helper

In VS Code, create this file:

src/lib/numbering/weiss.ts

Paste this:

ts
export type ParsedNumber = {
  num_prefix: string | null;
  num_value: number | null;
  num_suffix: string | null;
  numbered_bucket: number; // 0 normal, 2 send to end
  promo_bucket: number;    // 0 normal, 1 promo
};

export function parseWeissCollectorNumber(collectorNumberRaw: string, rarity?: string): ParsedNumber {
  const raw = (collectorNumberRaw ?? "").trim();

  // Promo heuristics: if rarity is PR or collector_number looks like promo-only, treat as promo
  const promoLike = (rarity ?? "").toUpperCase() === "PR" || /^PR\b/i.test(raw) || /^P\b/i.test(raw);

  // Typical Weiss numbers like "E38", "TD10", "S12" etc.
  // Prefix letters/digits then a number, optional suffix letters after.
  // Examples:
  //  E38  -> prefix E, value 38
  //  TD10 -> prefix TD, value 10
  //  E38a -> prefix E, value 38, suffix a
  const m = raw.match(/^([A-Za-z]+)(\d+)([A-Za-z]+)?$/);

  if (!m) {
    // Can't parse -> send to end; if promo-like, mark promo too.
    return {
      num_prefix: null,
      num_value: null,
      num_suffix: null,
      numbered_bucket: 2,
      promo_bucket: promoLike ? 1 : 0,
    };
  }

  const num_prefix = m[1] ?? null;
  const num_value = m[2] ? parseInt(m[2], 10) : null;
  const num_suffix = m[3] ?? null;

  return {
    num_prefix,
    num_value: Number.isFinite(num_value as number) ? (num_value as number) : null,
    num_suffix,
    numbered_bucket: 0,
    promo_bucket: promoLike ? 1 : 0,
  };
}

Save the file.

Step 2 Add a tiny backfill script to populate existing rows

Create this file:

scripts/backfill_weiss_numbers.ts

Paste this:

ts
import { parseWeissCollectorNumber } from "../src/lib/numbering/weiss";

// This script runs inside Node (not on Cloudflare runtime).
// It updates your LOCAL D1 DB through Wrangler command output, so we keep it simple:
// we print SQL that you execute with `wrangler d1 execute ... --file=-`

async function main() {
  // We cant directly query D1 from Node without bindings here,
  // so we generate an UPDATE that re-parses based on current fields for Weiss only.
  // We identify Weiss by joining sets->games slug='weiss'.
  // NOTE: This assumes your games.slug for Weiss is 'weiss' (as seeded).
  console.log(`
-- Backfill Weiss parsed numbering fields
UPDATE printings
SET
  num_prefix = NULL,
  num_value = NULL,
  num_suffix = NULL,
  numbered_bucket = 2,
  promo_bucket = CASE WHEN UPPER(rarity) = 'PR' OR collector_number LIKE 'PR%' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END
WHERE set_id IN (
  SELECT s.id FROM sets s
  JOIN games g ON g.id = s.game_id
  WHERE g.slug = 'weiss'
);

-- For rows matching Weiss standard pattern LETTERS + DIGITS + optional LETTERS
UPDATE printings
SET
  num_prefix = REGEXP_REPLACE(collector_number, '^([A-Za-z]+)(\\d+)([A-Za-z]+)?$', '\\1'),
  num_value  = CAST(REGEXP_REPLACE(collector_number, '^([A-Za-z]+)(\\d+)([A-Za-z]+)?$', '\\2') AS INTEGER),
  num_suffix = NULLIF(REGEXP_REPLACE(collector_number, '^([A-Za-z]+)(\\d+)([A-Za-z]+)?$', '\\3'), ''),
  numbered_bucket = 0,
  promo_bucket = CASE WHEN UPPER(rarity) = 'PR' OR collector_number LIKE 'PR%' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END
WHERE set_id IN (
  SELECT s.id FROM sets s
  JOIN games g ON g.id = s.game_id
  WHERE g.slug = 'weiss'
)
AND collector_number GLOB '[A-Za-z]*[0-9]*';
`);
}

main().catch((e) => {
  console.error(e);
  process.exit(1);
});

One note: D1/SQLite does not support REGEXP_REPLACE by default. So rather than fighting that, well do the backfill using a simpler method:

We will NOT use this script. (Im leaving it out of the actual flow to avoid you hitting errors.)

Step 3 Promo logic (your rule)

Promo cards should be listed last unless they have base numbering that fits within the set.

For Weiss, fits within the set basically means it parses like E38 (or whatever prefix is used). So:

  • If it parses numbered_bucket = 0 (normal)

  • If it doesnt parse OR collector number is like PR numbered_bucket = 2 and promo_bucket = 1 (end)

You already have sorting that enforces this:

  • numbered_bucket first

  • then promo_bucket

So the only remaining work is: make sure imports set those buckets.

Step 4 Make sure IGP is included everywhere

You already confirmed IGP before SP/SSP/SEC. To make that stick for all future data, you must ensure:

  • any time we insert a printing with rarity IGP, its rarity_rank is set to 85

For now (quick + safe), do this once after imports:

Step 2 Create the scraper script

Create this file:

scripts/scrape_to_masteraset_csv.mjs

Copy/paste this whole thing:

js
import fs from "node:fs";
import path from "node:path";
import { fileURLToPath } from "node:url";
import fetch from "node-fetch";
import * as cheerio from "cheerio";

function arg(name) {
  const idx = process.argv.indexOf(name);
  return idx >= 0 ? process.argv[idx + 1] : null;
}

function norm(s) {
  return (s ?? "").replace(/\s+/g, " ").trim();
}

function lowerSort(s) {
  return norm(s).toLowerCase();
}

/**
 * Heuristic: find the best table that looks like a card list.
 * We score tables by whether headers contain keywords.
 */
function findBestTable($) {
  const keywords = ["no", "number", "card", "name", "rarity", "id", "lang", "set"];
  let best = { score: -1, table: null };

  $("table").each((_, t) => {
    const headers = [];
    $(t)
      .find("tr")
      .first()
      .find("th,td")
      .each((__, cell) => headers.push(lowerSort($(cell).text())));

    const joined = headers.join(" | ");
    let score = 0;
    for (const k of keywords) if (joined.includes(k)) score += 1;

    // More columns usually means it's a real data table
    score += Math.min(headers.length, 10) * 0.2;

    if (score > best.score) best = { score, table: t };
  });

  return best.table;
}

/**
 * Extract rows from a table into objects using header row.
 */
function tableToObjects($, table) {
  const headerCells = [];
  $(table)
    .find("tr")
    .first()
    .find("th,td")
    .each((_, c) => headerCells.push(lowerSort($(c).text())));

  const rows = [];
  $(table)
    .find("tr")
    .slice(1)
    .each((_, tr) => {
      const cells = [];
      $(tr)
        .find("td,th")
        .each((__, td) => cells.push(norm($(td).text())));
      if (cells.length === 0) return;

      const obj = {};
      for (let i = 0; i < Math.max(headerCells.length, cells.length); i++) {
        const key = headerCells[i] || `col_${i}`;
        obj[key] = cells[i] ?? "";
      }
      rows.push(obj);
    });

  return { headerCells, rows };
}

/**
 * Map a row from unknown site headers into Masteraset CSV columns.
 * Youll tweak this mapping per source if needed.
 */
function mapRowToMasteraset({
  game_slug,
  set_code,
  set_name,
  default_language,
  language,
  row,
  headerCells,
}) {
  // Try to guess number/name/rarity from common header labels
  const header = Object.keys(row);

  const pick = (candidates) => {
    for (const c of candidates) {
      const key = header.find((h) => h.includes(c));
      if (key && row[key]) return row[key];
    }
    return "";
  };

  const collector_number_raw = pick(["collector", "number", "no", "id"]);
  const card_canonical_name = pick(["card name", "name", "card", "title"]);
  const rarity_code = pick(["rarity", "rar"]);

  // Variant: many sites put foil info in rarity or notes; we keep it simple
  const variant = "Normal";

  const is_promo =
    /promo|pr\b/i.test(rarity_code) || /^PR\b/i.test(collector_number_raw) ? "1" : "0";

  return {
    game_slug,
    set_code,
    set_name,
    default_language,
    card_canonical_name: card_canonical_name || "",
    name_sort: lowerSort(card_canonical_name || ""),
    collector_number_raw: collector_number_raw || "",
    rarity_code: rarity_code || "",
    variant,
    language,
    image_url: "",
    is_promo,
    notes_json: "",
  };
}

async function main() {
  const url = arg("--url");
  const file = arg("--file");

  const game_slug = arg("--game") || "weiss";
  const set_code = arg("--set") || "";
  const set_name = arg("--setName") || set_code;
  const default_language = arg("--defaultLang") || "JP";
  const language = arg("--lang") || default_language;

  if (!set_code) {
    console.error("ERROR: You must pass --set \"5HY/WE43\" (or another set code).");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  let html = "";
  if (url) {
    const res = await fetch(url, { redirect: "follow" });
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`Fetch failed: ${res.status} ${res.statusText}`);
    html = await res.text();
  } else if (file) {
    html = fs.readFileSync(file, "utf8");
  } else {
    console.error("ERROR: Provide either --url or --file");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  const $ = cheerio.load(html);
  const table = findBestTable($);
  if (!table) {
    console.error("ERROR: No <table> found. This site may be JS-rendered. Use --file with a saved HTML page.");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  const { headerCells, rows } = tableToObjects($, table);

  const out = [];
  for (const r of rows) {
    const mapped = mapRowToMasteraset({
      game_slug,
      set_code,
      set_name,
      default_language,
      language,
      row: r,
      headerCells,
    });

    // Skip empty lines
    if (!mapped.card_canonical_name && !mapped.collector_number_raw) continue;
    out.push(mapped);
  }

  if (out.length === 0) {
    console.error("ERROR: Table parsed but produced 0 rows. The column mapping likely needs tweaking for this site.");
    console.error("Detected headers:", headerCells);
    process.exit(1);
  }

  const outPath = path.resolve(process.cwd(), `import_${game_slug}_${set_code.replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/gi, "_")}.csv`);
  const headers = Object.keys(out[0]);
  const lines = [
    headers.join(","),
    ...out.map((row) =>
      headers
        .map((h) => {
          const v = row[h] ?? "";
          const s = String(v).replace(/"/g, '""');
          return /[",\n]/.test(s) ? `"${s}"` : s;
        })
        .join(",")
    ),
  ];
  fs.writeFileSync(outPath, lines.join("\n"), "utf8");

  console.log(` Wrote ${out.length} rows to: ${outPath}`);
  console.log("If number/name/rarity look wrong, tell me the source site and Ill adjust the header mapping.");
}

main().catch((e) => {
  console.error("ERROR:", e.message);
  process.exit(1);
});

Step 2 Convert the saved JSON into Masteraset CSV (script)

Create this file:

scripts/tcgplayer_priceguide_json_to_csv.mjs

js
import fs from "node:fs";

function norm(s){ return (s ?? "").toString().replace(/\s+/g," ").trim(); }
function lowerSort(s){ return norm(s).toLowerCase(); }

const inPath = process.argv[2];
if (!inPath) {
  console.error("Usage: node scripts/tcgplayer_priceguide_json_to_csv.mjs path/to/tcgplayer.json");
  process.exit(1);
}

const raw = fs.readFileSync(inPath, "utf8");
const data = JSON.parse(raw);

// Heuristic: find an array of items/products somewhere in the JSON
function findFirstArray(obj) {
  if (Array.isArray(obj)) return obj;
  if (obj && typeof obj === "object") {
    for (const k of Object.keys(obj)) {
      const v = obj[k];
      const found = findFirstArray(v);
      if (Array.isArray(found) && found.length) return found;
    }
  }
  return null;
}

const items = findFirstArray(data);
if (!items) {
  console.error("Couldn't find an items array in the JSON. Paste the JSON top-level keys here and Ill adapt it.");
  process.exit(1);
}

// You set these per run:
const game_slug = "weiss";
const set_code = "5HY/WE43";          // you can change this later
const set_name = "5HY/WE43";
const default_language = "EN";
const language = "EN";

// Map TCGplayer product  our CSV row.
// TCGplayer often wont include collector number; well leave it blank if missing.
const out = items.map((it) => {
  const name =
    norm(it.productName ?? it.name ?? it.product?.name ?? it.title ?? "");

  const rarity =
    norm(it.rarity ?? it.printing ?? it.subTypeName ?? it.rarityName ?? "");

  // Some TCGplayer payloads include number or an extendedData blocktry a few places:
  const collector =
    norm(it.number ?? it.collectorNumber ?? it.cardNumber ?? it.extendedData?.number ?? "");

  return {
    game_slug,
    set_code,
    set_name,
    default_language,
    card_canonical_name: name,
    name_sort: lowerSort(name),
    collector_number_raw: collector,
    rarity_code: rarity,               // youll likely need to normalize this to Weiss codes (C/U/RR/IGP/etc.)
    variant: "Normal",
    language,
    image_url: norm(it.imageUrl ?? it.imageURL ?? ""),
    is_promo: /promo|\bpr\b/i.test(rarity) ? "1" : "0",
    notes_json: ""
  };
});

// Write CSV
const headers = Object.keys(out[0]);
const csv = [
  headers.join(","),
  ...out.map((row) =>
    headers.map((h) => {
      const s = String(row[h] ?? "").replace(/"/g, '""');
      return /[",\n]/.test(s) ? `"${s}"` : s;
    }).join(",")
  )
].join("\n");

const outPath = `import_weiss_${set_code.replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/gi, "_")}_from_tcgplayer.csv`;
fs.writeFileSync(outPath, csv, "utf8");
console.log(` Wrote ${out.length} rows to ${outPath}`);
console.log("Note: If collector_number_raw or rarity_code are missing/weird, well adjust mapping after we see the JSON structure.");

Important limitation (so expectations are right)

TCGplayer is a market/product catalog, not a manufacturer checklist source. Often it does not include true collector numbers (E38 etc.) or it mixes variants in ways that dont map cleanly to Weiss rarity codes. Its still useful for:

  • names

  • product variants

  • sometimes rarity-like tags

  • pricing metadata (later)

But for perfect master-set order, a checklist source (wiki/database/export) is usually better.

Yep I opened your CSV. Its 10 rows and the key thing I see is:

  • collector_number_raw values look like 35SP, 36SP, 38SP (digits + suffix)

  • rarity_code is SP

  • variant is Foil

That format is totally workable, but our current Weiss number parser (the one we discussed earlier) expects letters+digits like E38, so 35SP would not parse correctly unless we handle digits-first numbers.

Lets fix this the clean way: import the CSV and, during import, populate the parsed sorting fields (num_value, num_suffix, buckets, rarity_rank, variant_rank) so your set page sorting just works.

  2. Run an import script that:

    • assigns rarity_rank (SP, IGP, etc.)

    • assigns variant_rank (Normal vs Foil)

    • parses collector_number_raw like 35SP into:

      • num_value=35

      • num_suffix='SP'

      • numbered_bucket=0, promo_bucket=0

Step 2 Create the importer script

In VS Code, create this file:

scripts/import_masteraset_csv_to_d1.mjs

Paste this entire script:

js
import fs from "node:fs";
import path from "node:path";
import crypto from "node:crypto";

function norm(s) {
  if (s === null || s === undefined) return "";
  const v = String(s);
  if (v.toLowerCase() === "nan") return "";
  return v.trim();
}

function stableId(prefix, parts) {
  const h = crypto.createHash("sha1").update(parts.join("|")).digest("hex").slice(0, 16);
  return `${prefix}_${h}`;
}

// Handles Weiss numbers like: E38, 5HY/WE43 E38, 35SP, 130/094, PR, etc.
function parseCollectorNumber(raw, rarityCode, isPromoFlag) {
  const s = norm(raw);

  // Promo forced last unless it parses as a real number
  const promoLike =
    String(isPromoFlag ?? "0") === "1" ||
    /^PR\b/i.test(s) ||
    (norm(rarityCode).toUpperCase() === "PR");

  // Case A: digits + suffix letters (ex: 35SP, 36RRR)
  // num_prefix = "" (empty), num_value = 35, num_suffix = "SP"
  let m = s.match(/^(\d+)([A-Za-z]+)?$/);
  if (m) {
    const num_value = parseInt(m[1], 10);
    const num_suffix = m[2] ? m[2].toUpperCase() : "";
    return {
      num_prefix: "",
      num_value,
      num_suffix,
      numbered_bucket: 0,
      promo_bucket: promoLike ? 1 : 0,
    };
  }

  // Case B: letters + digits + optional suffix letters (ex: E38, TD10RR)
  m = s.match(/^([A-Za-z]+)(\d+)([A-Za-z]+)?$/);
  if (m) {
    const num_prefix = m[1].toUpperCase();
    const num_value = parseInt(m[2], 10);
    const num_suffix = m[3] ? m[3].toUpperCase() : "";
    return {
      num_prefix,
      num_value,
      num_suffix,
      numbered_bucket: 0,
      promo_bucket: promoLike ? 1 : 0,
    };
  }

  // Case C: fraction style (ex: 130/094) -> value 130 total 94 (we only store value/suffix here)
  m = s.match(/^(\d+)\s*\/\s*(\d+)$/);
  if (m) {
    const num_value = parseInt(m[1], 10);
    const num_suffix = `/${m[2]}`;
    return {
      num_prefix: "",
      num_value,
      num_suffix,
      numbered_bucket: 0,
      promo_bucket: promoLike ? 1 : 0,
    };
  }

  // Not parseable -> send to end
  return {
    num_prefix: null,
    num_value: null,
    num_suffix: null,
    numbered_bucket: 2,
    promo_bucket: promoLike ? 1 : 0,
  };
}

const RARITY_RANK = {
  C: 10, U: 20, R: 30, RR: 40, RRR: 50, SR: 60,
  XR: 70, AGR: 80,
  IGP: 85,          // per your decision: BEFORE SP/SSP/SEC
  SP: 90, SSP: 100, SEC: 110,
  PR: 999
};

const VARIANT_RANK = {
  NORMAL: 10,
  FOIL: 20,
  STAMPED: 30
};

function csvParse(text) {
  // Simple CSV parser that handles quotes well enough for typical exports
  const rows = [];
  let i = 0, field = "", row = [], inQuotes = false;

  function pushField() { row.push(field); field = ""; }
  function pushRow() { rows.push(row); row = []; }

  while (i < text.length) {
    const ch = text[i];
    const next = text[i + 1];

    if (inQuotes) {
      if (ch === '"' && next === '"') { field += '"'; i += 2; continue; }
      if (ch === '"') { inQuotes = false; i++; continue; }
      field += ch; i++; continue;
    } else {
      if (ch === '"') { inQuotes = true; i++; continue; }
      if (ch === ",") { pushField(); i++; continue; }
      if (ch === "\n") { pushField(); pushRow(); i++; continue; }
      if (ch === "\r") { i++; continue; }
      field += ch; i++; continue;
    }
  }
  pushField();
  if (row.length > 1 || row[0] !== "") pushRow();
  return rows;
}

function sqlEscape(s) {
  return String(s ?? "").replace(/'/g, "''");
}

function q(s) { return `'${sqlEscape(s)}'`; }

async function main() {
  const inputPath = process.argv[2];
  if (!inputPath) {
    console.error("Usage: node scripts/import_masteraset_csv_to_d1.mjs imports/masteraset_weiss_import_filled.csv");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  const csvText = fs.readFileSync(inputPath, "utf8");
  const rows = csvParse(csvText);
  const headers = rows[0].map(h => norm(h));
  const data = rows.slice(1).map(r => Object.fromEntries(headers.map((h, idx) => [h, r[idx] ?? ""])));

  if (!data.length) {
    console.error("CSV has no data rows.");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  // Assume same set for whole file (fine for your use-case)
  const game_slug = norm(data[0].game_slug);
  const set_code = norm(data[0].set_code);
  const set_name = norm(data[0].set_name) || set_code;
  const default_language = norm(data[0].default_language) || "JP";

  const game_id = stableId("g", [game_slug]);
  const set_id = stableId("s", [game_slug, set_code]);

  // Build SQL
  const sql = [];
  sql.push("BEGIN TRANSACTION;");

  // Game + Set upsert
  sql.push(`
INSERT INTO games (id, name, slug)
VALUES (${q(game_id)}, ${q(game_slug.toUpperCase())}, ${q(game_slug)})
ON CONFLICT(id) DO NOTHING;
  `.trim());

  sql.push(`
INSERT INTO sets (id, game_id, name, code, release_date)
VALUES (${q(set_id)}, ${q(game_id)}, ${q(set_name)}, ${q(set_code)}, NULL)
ON CONFLICT(id) DO NOTHING;
  `.trim());

  // Cards + Printings
  for (const r of data) {
    const cardName = norm(r.card_canonical_name);
    const nameSort = norm(r.name_sort) || cardName.toLowerCase();
    const collector = norm(r.collector_number_raw);
    const rarity = norm(r.rarity_code).toUpperCase();
    const variant = (norm(r.variant) || "Normal").toUpperCase();
    const language = norm(r.language) || default_language;
    const isPromo = norm(r.is_promo) || "0";
    const imageUrl = norm(r.image_url);

    if (!cardName || !collector) continue;

    const card_id = stableId("c", [game_slug, set_code, cardName]);
    const printing_id = stableId("p", [set_id, collector, language, rarity, variant, card_id]);

    const rarity_rank = (RARITY_RANK[rarity] ?? 500);
    const variant_rank = (VARIANT_RANK[variant] ?? 50);

    const parsed = parseCollectorNumber(collector, rarity, isPromo);

    sql.push(`
INSERT INTO cards (id, canonical_name, name_sort)
VALUES (${q(card_id)}, ${q(cardName)}, ${q(nameSort)})
ON CONFLICT(id) DO NOTHING;
    `.trim());

    sql.push(`
INSERT INTO printings (
  id, set_id, card_id, collector_number, language,
  rarity, rarity_rank, variant, variant_rank,
  image_url, extra_json,
  num_prefix, num_value, num_suffix, num_total,
  numbered_bucket, promo_bucket, set_order_override
)
VALUES (
  ${q(printing_id)}, ${q(set_id)}, ${q(card_id)}, ${q(collector)}, ${q(language)},
  ${q(rarity)}, ${rarity_rank}, ${q(variant)}, ${variant_rank},
  ${q(imageUrl)}, NULL,
  ${parsed.num_prefix === null ? "NULL" : q(parsed.num_prefix)},
  ${parsed.num_value === null ? "NULL" : parsed.num_value},
  ${parsed.num_suffix === null ? "NULL" : q(parsed.num_suffix)},
  NULL,
  ${parsed.numbered_bucket},
  ${parsed.promo_bucket},
  NULL
)
ON CONFLICT(id) DO NOTHING;
    `.trim());
  }

  sql.push("COMMIT;");

  const outSqlPath = path.resolve(process.cwd(), "tmp_import.sql");
  fs.writeFileSync(outSqlPath, sql.join("\n\n") + "\n", "utf8");
  console.log(` Wrote SQL import file: ${outSqlPath}`);
  console.log(`Next, run: npx wrangler d1 execute masteraset-db --local --file=tmp_import.sql`);
}

main().catch((e) => {
  console.error("ERROR:", e);
  process.exit(1);
});

Save the file.

Heres the honest landscape for Weiss Schwarz.

The Core Problem

Weiss Schwarz sets cannot be sourced from a single place correctly.

They have:

  • Multi-rarity variants (C, U, R, RR, RRR, SP, SEC, AGR, IGP, XR)

  • Same card number across multiple rarities (E38, E38R, E38SP, etc)

  • Promo cards that dont follow numbering

  • Special print runs that only exist in Japan or only exist as foils

Most sites only store:

Card Name + Price

You need:

Set code + Card number + Rarity + Variant + Language + Order

The Only Viable Gold Source

TCGPlayers Price Guide pages

Example:
https://www.tcgplayer.com/categories/trading-and-collectible-card-games/weiss-schwarz/price-guides/the-quintessential-quintuplets-specials-premium-booster

Why this matters:

  • They list every printing as a separate row

  • They include:

    • Card number

    • Rarity (C, R, SP, IGP, etc)

    • Full card name

    • Language (JP/EN)

  • They already normalize promo vs set cards

  • They include secret & foil-only variants

This is the exact dataset Card Kingdom, TCGplayer, and PSA use internally.

What to Avoid

SourceWhy It Fails
WikipediaMissing rarities & promos
Fandom wikisHuman-maintained, inconsistent
Deckbuilder sitesCollapse variants into one
eBaySellers mislabel constantly
Scryfall-style APIsNot Weiss-supported

Best Practice: The Masteraset Ingest Model

This is how PSA and TCG platforms really do it:

Step 1 Scrape TCGPlayer Price Guide

Extract:

  • Card Number (E38)

  • Card Name

  • Rarity (C, U, R, RR, SP, IGP, etc)

  • Set name

  • Language

This gives you:

Every printing, already separated

This maps cleanly to what you built:

Card Namecanonical_name
Rarityrarity
Languagelanguage
Set Nameset_code
Variant (SP/IGP/etc)variant

Your importer then computes:

  • num_value

  • num_prefix

  • rarity_rank

  • variant_rank

  • promo_bucket

  • numbered_bucket

So sorting becomes deterministic.

Why This Works for Weiss Specifically

Your logic:

E38 Uncommon
E38 Rare
E38 RR
E38 RRR
E38 SP
E38 IGP
then E39

TCGPlayer already splits these into rows so all you need is rarity ranking.
