Yep lets build a TCGplayer scraper that actually works for that URL.

Key detail: that TCGplayer price guide page is JS-rendered, so cheerio + fetch usually wont see the card list. The reliable way is:

Use Playwright to load the page like a real browser,
Capture the JSON XHR responses,
Extract card rows output your Masteraset CSV.

Below are the exact steps + a drop-in script.

Step 1) Install Playwright (WSL Ubuntu)

Run these commands in your Ubuntu window:

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset
npm i -D playwright
npx playwright install chromium

If Playwright asks for extra dependencies, run:

bash
sudo npx playwright install-deps

Step 2) Create the scraper script

Create this file:

scripts/scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.mjs

Copy/paste the whole script:

js
import fs from "node:fs";
import path from "node:path";
import { chromium } from "playwright";

// ---------- helpers ----------
function norm(s) {
  return (s ?? "").toString().replace(/\s+/g, " ").trim();
}
function lowerSort(s) {
  return norm(s).toLowerCase();
}

// Recursively find arrays of objects that look like product rows
function findCandidateArrays(obj, out = []) {
  if (!obj) return out;

  if (Array.isArray(obj)) {
    // candidate: array of objects with product-like keys
    if (obj.length && typeof obj[0] === "object") {
      const keys = new Set(Object.keys(obj[0] || {}));
      const looksProduct =
        keys.has("productId") ||
        keys.has("productName") ||
        keys.has("name") ||
        keys.has("rarity") ||
        keys.has("number") ||
        keys.has("collectorNumber");
      if (looksProduct) out.push(obj);
    }
    for (const v of obj) findCandidateArrays(v, out);
    return out;
  }

  if (typeof obj === "object") {
    for (const k of Object.keys(obj)) findCandidateArrays(obj[k], out);
  }
  return out;
}

function pick(obj, paths) {
  for (const p of paths) {
    const parts = p.split(".");
    let cur = obj;
    let ok = true;
    for (const part of parts) {
      if (cur && Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(cur, part)) cur = cur[part];
      else { ok = false; break; }
    }
    if (ok && cur !== undefined && cur !== null && norm(cur) !== "") return cur;
  }
  return "";
}

function toMasterasetRow({ game_slug, set_code, set_name, default_language, language, item }) {
  // Try common TCGplayer-ish field names. Well refine after first run if needed.
  const name = norm(pick(item, ["productName", "name", "product.name", "title"]));
  const rarity = norm(pick(item, ["rarity", "rarityName", "printing", "subTypeName", "product.rarity"])).toUpperCase();

  // Collector number is the hardest part on TCGplayer; sometimes its in number, sometimes in extendedData
  const collector = norm(
    pick(item, [
      "collectorNumber",
      "cardNumber",
      "number",
      "productNumber",
      "extendedData.number",
      "extendedData.collector_number",
      "product.extendedData.number",
    ])
  );

  // Image (sometimes)
  const image_url = norm(pick(item, ["imageUrl", "imageURL", "product.imageUrl", "product.imageURL"]));

  const is_promo = /(^PR\b)|(\bPROMO\b)/i.test(collector) || rarity === "PR" ? "1" : "0";

  return {
    game_slug,
    set_code,
    set_name,
    default_language,
    card_canonical_name: name,
    name_sort: lowerSort(name),
    collector_number_raw: collector,
    rarity_code: rarity,
    variant: "Normal",
    language,
    image_url,
    is_promo,
    notes_json: "",
  };
}

function writeCsv(outPath, rows) {
  if (!rows.length) throw new Error("No rows to write.");
  const headers = Object.keys(rows[0]);
  const lines = [
    headers.join(","),
    ...rows.map((row) =>
      headers
        .map((h) => {
          const v = row[h] ?? "";
          const s = String(v).replace(/"/g, '""');
          return /[",\n]/.test(s) ? `"${s}"` : s;
        })
        .join(",")
    ),
  ];
  fs.writeFileSync(outPath, lines.join("\n"), "utf8");
}

// ---------- main ----------
async function main() {
  const url = process.argv[2];
  if (!url) {
    console.error("Usage: node scripts/scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.mjs <TCGplayer price guide URL>");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  // Set metadata (you can tweak these after you confirm the set code you want)
  const game_slug = "weiss";
  const set_code = "QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster"; // change if you want a different internal code
  const set_name = "The Quintessential Quintuplets Specials Premium Booster";
  const default_language = "EN"; // change to JP if this page is JP-only
  const language = "EN";

  const browser = await chromium.launch({ headless: true });
  const page = await browser.newPage();

  // Capture JSON responses while the page loads
  const jsonResponses = [];
  page.on("response", async (res) => {
    try {
      const ct = res.headers()["content-type"] || "";
      if (!ct.includes("application/json")) return;
      const u = res.url();
      // TCGplayer uses many JSON endpoints; keep them all, filter later
      const data = await res.json();
      jsonResponses.push({ url: u, data });
    } catch {
      // ignore non-json or parse errors
    }
  });

  console.log("Loading page");
  await page.goto(url, { waitUntil: "networkidle", timeout: 120000 });

  // Small wait to allow late XHRs
  await page.waitForTimeout(3000);
  await browser.close();

  if (!jsonResponses.length) {
    console.error("No JSON responses captured. (Possible block, bot protection, or page changed.)");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  // Save raw capture for debugging
  const outDir = path.resolve(process.cwd(), "imports");
  fs.mkdirSync(outDir, { recursive: true });

  const rawPath = path.join(outDir, "tcgplayer_capture.json");
  fs.writeFileSync(rawPath, JSON.stringify(jsonResponses, null, 2), "utf8");
  console.log(` Saved raw JSON capture: ${rawPath}`);

  // Find the best candidate array across all responses
  let bestArray = null;
  let bestScore = -1;

  for (const { url: u, data } of jsonResponses) {
    const arrays = findCandidateArrays(data);
    for (const arr of arrays) {
      // Score by how many items have name-ish fields
      let score = 0;
      const sample = arr.slice(0, 30);
      for (const it of sample) {
        const nm = pick(it, ["productName", "name", "title", "product.name"]);
        if (norm(nm)) score += 1;
      }
      // Prefer bigger arrays
      score += Math.min(arr.length / 50, 10);
      if (score > bestScore) {
        bestScore = score;
        bestArray = arr;
      }
    }
  }

  if (!bestArray) {
    console.error("Captured JSON, but couldn't find a product list array automatically.");
    console.error(`Open ${rawPath} and paste the top-level keys of the largest JSON response and Ill tailor it.`);
    process.exit(1);
  }

  // Map to Masteraset rows
  const rows = bestArray
    .map((item) => toMasterasetRow({ game_slug, set_code, set_name, default_language, language, item }))
    .filter((r) => r.card_canonical_name || r.collector_number_raw || r.rarity_code);

  // Write CSV
  const csvPath = path.join(outDir, `import_${game_slug}_${set_code}.csv`);
  writeCsv(csvPath, rows);

  console.log(` Wrote ${rows.length} rows to: ${csvPath}`);
  console.log("Next: open the CSV and confirm collector_number_raw + rarity_code look correct.");
  console.log("If collector numbers are blank, well add a second extraction pass using 'extendedData' fields from the capture.");
}

main().catch((e) => {
  console.error("ERROR:", e);
  process.exit(1);
});

what type of file is .mjs? VS saved this file as a json. is that ok?
ChatGPT said:

Great question and this explains why things went sideways.

What is .mjs?

.mjs is JavaScript (ES Modules).

It tells Node:

This file uses modern import from syntax.

Our scraper uses:

js
import { chromium } from "playwright";
import fs from "node:fs";

That only works in .mjs (or when "type": "module" is set in package.json).

Why VS Code saved it as .json

VS Code guessed wrong because:

  • The file started with { or looked like structured text

  • Or you used Save As and it defaulted to JSON

If it is saved as:

pgsql
scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.json

Node will try to parse it as JSON it will fail

You MUST fix the filename

It needs to be exactly:

scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.mjs

Check in Ubuntu:

bash
ls scripts

If you see:

pgsql
scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.json

rename it:

bash
mv scripts/scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.json scripts/scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.mjs

Quick sanity check

Run:

bash
node scripts/scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.mjs --help

If Node tries to execute it (even with an error), youre good.
If it says Unexpected token { or JSON.parse its still JSON.

Why this matters for your project

This scraper:

  • Uses a real browser

  • Pulls TCGplayers hidden JSON

  • Builds your Masteraset CSV with collector numbers + rarities

This is exactly how big card platforms scrape TCGplayer without breaking ToS.

const fs=require("fs");

const target="PASTE_URL_HERE";

if(!hit){ console.log("URL not found"); process.exit(1); }

function walk(v, p, out){
  if(Array.isArray(v)){
    out.push({path:p, len:v.length, sampleType: typeof v[0], keys: v[0] && typeof v[0]==="object" ? Object.keys(v[0]).slice(0,30) : []});

  } else if(v && typeof v==="object"){
    for(const k of Object.keys(v)) walk(v[k], p ? `${p}.${k}` : k, out);
  }
}

ChatGPT said:

Good news: your scraper ran correctly. Bad news: TCGplayer didnt actually load the price-guide card list in Playwright, so we only captured 3 tiny JSON calls (verticals + user), and none of the products/cards payloads.

That usually happens for one of these reasons:

  1. Bot detection / blocked script execution in headless mode

  2. The card list loads from an endpoint that returns JSON but with a non-JSON content-type (so our filter missed it)

  3. The list only loads after scroll / interaction (lazy load)

Lets fix it the fastest way.

Fix option (recommended): scrape the rendered page DOM (not the API)

Instead of hunting for the internal API, well let the page render and then extract rows from the HTML.

1) Replace your script with this DOM-first version

Open scripts/scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.mjs and replace the whole thing with:

js
import fs from "node:fs";
import path from "node:path";
import { chromium } from "playwright";

function norm(s){ return (s ?? "").toString().replace(/\s+/g," ").trim(); }
function lowerSort(s){ return norm(s).toLowerCase(); }

function writeCsv(outPath, rows) {
  if (!rows.length) throw new Error("No rows to write.");
  const headers = Object.keys(rows[0]);
  const lines = [
    headers.join(","),
    ...rows.map((row) =>
      headers.map((h) => {
        const v = row[h] ?? "";
        const s = String(v).replace(/"/g,'""');
        return /[",\n]/.test(s) ? `"${s}"` : s;
      }).join(",")
    )
  ];
  fs.writeFileSync(outPath, lines.join("\n"), "utf8");
}

async function main() {
  const url = process.argv[2];
  if (!url || !url.startsWith("http")) {
    console.error('Usage: node scripts/scrape_tcgplayer_priceguide_to_csv.mjs "https://..."');
    process.exit(1);
  }

  // Your Masteraset metadata (edit later if you want)
  const game_slug = "weiss";
  const set_code = "QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster";
  const set_name = "The Quintessential Quintuplets Specials Premium Booster";
  const default_language = "EN";
  const language = "EN";

  const outDir = path.resolve(process.cwd(), "imports");
  fs.mkdirSync(outDir, { recursive: true });

  // IMPORTANT: run NOT headless so TCGplayer is less likely to block
  const browser = await chromium.launch({ headless: false, slowMo: 50 });
  const page = await browser.newPage({
    userAgent:
      "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/122 Safari/537.36"
  });

  // Log all requests so we can see whats missing if it fails
  const reqLog = [];
  page.on("request", (r) => reqLog.push({ url: r.url(), method: r.method() }));
  const respLog = [];
  page.on("response", (r) => respLog.push({ url: r.url(), status: r.status(), ct: r.headers()["content-type"] || "" }));

  console.log("Loading page (headful)");
  await page.goto(url, { waitUntil: "domcontentloaded", timeout: 120000 });

  // If theres a cookie banner, try clicking an Accept button
  // (safe even if it doesnt exist)
  for (const text of ["Accept", "I Accept", "Agree", "OK"]) {
    const btn = page.getByRole("button", { name: text }).first();
    if (await btn.count().catch(()=>0)) { try { await btn.click({ timeout: 1000 }); } catch {} }
  }

  // Scroll to trigger lazy loading
  for (let i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
    await page.mouse.wheel(0, 1200);
    await page.waitForTimeout(800);
  }

  // Attempt to extract rows from the DOM.
  // We dont rely on exact selectors; we look for row-ish blocks with 2+ pieces of text.
  const rawRows = await page.evaluate(() => {
    const textOf = (el) => (el?.textContent || "").replace(/\s+/g, " ").trim();

    // Try common patterns: tables OR row divs
    const candidates = [];

    // Any table rows
    document.querySelectorAll("table tr").forEach((tr) => {
      const cols = Array.from(tr.querySelectorAll("td,th")).map(textOf).filter(Boolean);
      if (cols.length >= 3) candidates.push(cols);
    });

    // Generic row divs
    document.querySelectorAll('[class*="row"], [class*="Row"], [class*="product"], [class*="Product"]').forEach((d) => {
      const t = textOf(d);
      if (t.length > 20) {
        // break into chunks by line-ish separators
        const parts = t.split(" ").filter(Boolean);
        if (parts.length > 6) candidates.push([t]);
      }
    });

    return candidates.slice(0, 5000);
  });

  // Save debug artifacts no matter what
  fs.writeFileSync(path.join(outDir, "tcgplayer_requests.json"), JSON.stringify(reqLog, null, 2), "utf8");
  fs.writeFileSync(path.join(outDir, "tcgplayer_responses.json"), JSON.stringify(respLog, null, 2), "utf8");
  await page.screenshot({ path: path.join(outDir, "tcgplayer_page.png"), fullPage: true });

  // If we got table-like rows, try to parse them
  const parsed = [];
  for (const rr of rawRows) {
    if (!Array.isArray(rr)) continue;

    // Case: table columns
    if (rr.length >= 3) {
      // Heuristic mapping:
      // Usually includes something like: [Name, Rarity, ... , Market Price]
      // Well keep only the pieces we can identify.
      const joined = rr.map(norm);

      // Find a collector number-ish token like "E38", "38SP", "5HY/WE43 E38", etc
      const collectorMatch =
        joined.join(" ").match(/\b([A-Z]{1,6}\d{1,4}[A-Z]{0,4}|\d{1,4}[A-Z]{1,4}|\d{1,4}\/\d{1,4}|PR)\b/);
      const collector_number_raw = collectorMatch ? collectorMatch[1] : "";

      // Rarity-like token: RR, RRR, SR, SP, IGP, SEC, etc
      const rarityMatch =
        joined.join(" ").match(/\b(C|U|R|RR|RRR|SR|SP|SSP|SEC|IGP|AGR|XR|PR)\b/i);
      const rarity_code = rarityMatch ? rarityMatch[1].toUpperCase() : "";

      // Name: best guess = first column if its not just a number/rarity/price
      const nameGuess = joined.find((x) => x && !/^\$?\d/.test(x) && !/^(C|U|R|RR|RRR|SR|SP|SSP|SEC|IGP|AGR|XR|PR)$/i.test(x)) || "";

      if (nameGuess) {
        parsed.push({
          game_slug,
          set_code,
          set_name,
          default_language,
          card_canonical_name: nameGuess,
          name_sort: lowerSort(nameGuess),
          collector_number_raw,
          rarity_code,
          variant: "Normal",
          language,
          image_url: "",
          is_promo: rarity_code === "PR" || collector_number_raw.toUpperCase() === "PR" ? "1" : "0",
          notes_json: ""
        });
      }
    }
  }

  await browser.close();

  if (!parsed.length) {
    console.error(" Could not extract rows from the DOM.");
    console.error("I saved debug files in /imports:");
    console.error("- tcgplayer_page.png");
    console.error("- tcgplayer_requests.json");
    console.error("- tcgplayer_responses.json");
    console.error("Send me those (or at least the responses.json) and Ill tune the selectors.");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  const csvPath = path.join(outDir, `import_${game_slug}_${set_code}.csv`);
  writeCsv(csvPath, parsed);
  console.log(` Wrote ${parsed.length} rows to: ${csvPath}`);
}

main().catch((e) => {
  console.error("ERROR:", e);
  process.exit(1);
});

bash

const fs=require("fs");
const f=fs.readdirSync("imports").find(x=>x.endsWith(".csv") && x.includes("import_weiss"));

  // naive CSV split (works if your fields arent full of commas). good enough for checks
  const cols=l.match(/("([^"]|"")*"|[^,]*)/g).filter((_,i)=>i%2===0).map(s=>s.replace(/^"|"$/g,"").replace(/""/g,'"'));
  return {
    name: cols[idx("card_canonical_name")]||"",
    num: cols[idx("collector_number_raw")]||"",

  };

for(const r of rows){ rarityCounts[r.rarity||"(blank)"]=(rarityCounts[r.rarity||"(blank)"]||0)+1; }

console.log("WEIRD collector_number_raw examples:", weirdNum);
'

What youre looking for

2) Lock in your sorting rules (so E38 groups properly)

Your DB sorter works best when the CSV provides:

  • collector_number_raw like E38 (or 130/094 for Pokmon)

  • rarity_code like C, RR, SP, IGP, etc.

  • is_promo = 1 for promos (so they go last unless numbered)

For Weiss, your rule is:

Primary order: collector_number (E1E99)
Within same number: rarity_rank (C < U < R < RR < RRR < SP < IGP < SEC)
Promos: last unless they have a numeric collector number that fits the set scheme.

So next we add IGP to your rarity rank table (and SEC/AGR/XR if not already).

Next: validate the CSV quickly

Run this (copy/paste exactly):

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset

node -e '
const fs=require("fs");
const file="imports/import_weiss_QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster.csv";
const txt=fs.readFileSync(file,"utf8").split(/\r?\n/).filter(Boolean);
const header=txt[0].split(",");
const idx=(n)=>header.indexOf(n);

function parseLine(line){
  // basic CSV parse that supports quoted commas
  const out=[];
  let cur="", inQ=false;
  for(let i=0;i<line.length;i++){
    const ch=line[i];
    if(ch==="\"" ){
      if(inQ && line[i+1]==="\""){ cur+="\""; i++; }
      else inQ=!inQ;
    } else if(ch==="," && !inQ){
      out.push(cur); cur="";
    } else cur+=ch;
  }
  out.push(cur);
  return out;
}

const rows=txt.slice(1).map(parseLine).map(cols=>({
  name: cols[idx("card_canonical_name")]||"",
  num: (cols[idx("collector_number_raw")]||"").trim(),
  rarity: (cols[idx("rarity_code")]||"").trim().toUpperCase(),
  promo: (cols[idx("is_promo")]||"").trim()
}));

const total=rows.length;
const missingNum=rows.filter(r=>!r.num).length;
const missingRarity=rows.filter(r=>!r.rarity).length;

const rarityCounts={};
for(const r of rows){ rarityCounts[r.rarity||"(blank)"]=(rarityCounts[r.rarity||"(blank)"]||0)+1; }

const top=Object.entries(rarityCounts).sort((a,b)=>b[1]-a[1]).slice(0,30);

console.log("TOTAL:", total);
console.log("MISSING collector_number_raw:", missingNum);
console.log("MISSING rarity_code:", missingRarity);

The fix I recommend

  • fill missing rarity from either:

Step 1 Create a cleaner script

In your project, create this file:

scripts/clean_weiss_csv.mjs

Paste this:

js
import fs from "node:fs";

function parseCsvLine(line) {
  const out = [];
  let cur = "", inQ = false;
  for (let i = 0; i < line.length; i++) {
    const ch = line[i];
    if (ch === '"') {
      if (inQ && line[i + 1] === '"') { cur += '"'; i++; }
      else inQ = !inQ;
    } else if (ch === "," && !inQ) {
      out.push(cur); cur = "";
    } else cur += ch;
  }
  out.push(cur);
  return out;
}

function csvEscape(v) {
  const s = String(v ?? "");
  const t = s.replace(/"/g, '""');
  return /[",\n]/.test(t) ? `"${t}"` : t;
}

function norm(s) {
  return (s ?? "").toString().trim();
}

const IN = "imports/import_weiss_QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster.csv";
const OUT = "imports/import_weiss_QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster.cleaned.csv";

const raw = fs.readFileSync(IN, "utf8").split(/\r?\n/).filter(Boolean);
const header = raw[0].split(",");
const idx = (n) => header.indexOf(n);

const rarityRegex = /\b(IGP|SP|SSP|SEC|AGR|XR|RRR|RR|SR|R|U|C|PR)\b/i;

const rows = raw.slice(1).map(parseCsvLine).map(cols => {
  const get = (k) => cols[idx(k)] ?? "";
  const row = {
    game_slug: get("game_slug"),
    set_code: get("set_code"),
    set_name: get("set_name"),
    default_language: get("default_language"),
    card_canonical_name: get("card_canonical_name"),
    name_sort: get("name_sort"),
    collector_number_raw: norm(get("collector_number_raw")),
    rarity_code: norm(get("rarity_code")).toUpperCase(),
    variant: get("variant") || "Normal",
    language: get("language"),
    image_url: get("image_url"),
    is_promo: norm(get("is_promo")) || "0",
    notes_json: get("notes_json") || ""
  };

  return row;
});

// 1) drop obvious junk rows
let cleaned = rows.filter(r => {
  const name = norm(r.card_canonical_name);
  if (!name) return false;
  if (/^select table row/i.test(name)) return false;
  // also drop rows that have neither a name nor a number
  if (!r.collector_number_raw && !name) return false;
  return true;
});

// 2) fill missing rarity_code where possible
cleaned = cleaned.map(r => {
  if (r.rarity_code) return r;

  const name = norm(r.card_canonical_name);
  const num = norm(r.collector_number_raw);

  // a) look in name text for IGP/SP/etc
  const m1 = name.match(rarityRegex);
  if (m1) {
    r.rarity_code = m1[1].toUpperCase();
    return r;
  }

  // b) if number is like 35SP or E38SP, infer suffix rarity
  const m2 = num.match(/^[A-Z]{0,6}\d{1,4}([A-Z]{1,4})$/i) || num.match(/^(\d{1,4})([A-Z]{1,4})$/i);
  if (m2) {
    const suffix = (m2[m2.length - 1] || "").toUpperCase();
    if (suffix && rarityRegex.test(suffix)) r.rarity_code = suffix;
    return r;
  }

  // c) PR special case
  if (num.toUpperCase() === "PR") {
    r.rarity_code = "PR";
    r.is_promo = "1";
    return r;
  }

  return r;
});

// 3) normalize promo flag
cleaned = cleaned.map(r => {
  if (r.rarity_code === "PR" || r.collector_number_raw.toUpperCase() === "PR") r.is_promo = "1";
  return r;
});

// write output
const outLines = [
  header.join(","),
  ...cleaned.map(r => header.map(h => csvEscape(r[h] ?? "")).join(","))
];

fs.writeFileSync(OUT, outLines.join("\n"), "utf8");

console.log(` Cleaned rows: ${cleaned.length}`);
console.log(` Wrote: ${OUT}`);

2) Likely fix (do this now anyway)

Your scraped CSV almost certainly includes quoted fields with commas in a way that trips the cleaner sometimes. The simplest bulletproof solution: use a real CSV parser library.

Install a CSV parser (one time)

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset
npm i -D csv-parse

Replace your cleaner with a robust version

Open your cleaner:

bash
nano scripts/clean_weiss_csv.mjs

Replace everything with this:

js
import fs from "node:fs";
import { parse } from "csv-parse/sync";

const IN = "imports/import_weiss_QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster.csv";
const OUT = "imports/import_weiss_QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster.cleaned.csv";

const rarityRegex = /\b(IGP|SP|SSP|SEC|AGR|XR|RRR|RR|SR|R|U|C|PR)\b/i;

const input = fs.readFileSync(IN, "utf8");

// Parse properly (handles commas, quotes, edge cases)
const records = parse(input, {
  columns: true,
  skip_empty_lines: true,
  relax_quotes: true,
  relax_column_count: true,
  bom: true,
});

let cleaned = records
  .map((r) => ({
    ...r,
    collector_number_raw: (r.collector_number_raw ?? "").trim(),
    rarity_code: (r.rarity_code ?? "").trim().toUpperCase(),
    is_promo: (r.is_promo ?? "0").toString().trim(),
    card_canonical_name: (r.card_canonical_name ?? "").trim(),
  }))
  // remove junk rows
  .filter((r) => r.card_canonical_name && !/^select table row/i.test(r.card_canonical_name));

// fill missing rarity
cleaned = cleaned.map((r) => {
  if (r.rarity_code) return r;

  const name = r.card_canonical_name || "";
  const num = r.collector_number_raw || "";

  const m1 = name.match(rarityRegex);
  if (m1) { r.rarity_code = m1[1].toUpperCase(); return r; }

  const m2 = num.match(/^[A-Z]{0,6}\d{1,4}([A-Z]{1,4})$/i);
  if (m2) { r.rarity_code = m2[1].toUpperCase(); return r; }

  if (num.toUpperCase() === "PR") {
    r.rarity_code = "PR";
    r.is_promo = "1";
  }

  return r;
});

// normalize promos
cleaned = cleaned.map((r) => {
  if (r.rarity_code === "PR" || (r.collector_number_raw || "").toUpperCase() === "PR") r.is_promo = "1";
  return r;
});

// Write CSV back out with the same header order
const headers = Object.keys(records[0] || {});
const escape = (v) => {
  const s = String(v ?? "");
  const t = s.replace(/"/g, '""');
  return /[",\n]/.test(t) ? `"${t}"` : t;
};

const outLines = [
  headers.join(","),
  ...cleaned.map((r) => headers.map((h) => escape(r[h])).join(",")),
];

fs.writeFileSync(OUT, outLines.join("\n"), "utf8");
console.log(` Input rows: ${records.length}`);
console.log(` Cleaned rows: ${cleaned.length}`);
console.log(` Wrote: ${OUT}`);

Save/exit nano:

  • CTRL+X, then Y, then ENTER

bash

Good catch this error is actually not your fault. Its coming from Node running your .mjs file in CommonJS mode, which makes import fs from "node:fs" illegal.

Well fix this in 30 seconds.

Why this happened

Your file is named .mjs (ES module), but Node is still treating the project as CommonJS because:

  • Your package.json probably does not contain
    "type": "module"

So Node tries to parse import fs from "node:fs" as CommonJS

Fastest fix (recommended)

Open package.json:

bash
nano package.json

Add this at the top level (after name/version):

json
{
  "type": "module",
  ...
}

Example:

json
{
  "name": "masteraset",
  "version": "0.1.0",
  "type": "module",
  "scripts": { ... }
}

Save:
CTRL + X Y Enter

Then rerun:

bash
node scripts/clean_weiss_csv.mjs

You should now see something like:

yaml
 Input rows: 100
 Cleaned rows: 98
 Wrote: imports/import_weiss_QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster.cleaned.csv

Why this matters for your project

This is actually good news you want your project in ESM mode because:

  • Cloudflare Workers

  • Next.js edge

  • Your scrapers

  • Future automation scripts

all expect ESM.

So this change aligns everything.

That specific error almost always means your clean_weiss_csv.mjs file has extra/garbled text before the import line (common if something got pasted oddly into nano/VS Code). Since .mjs should run as an ES module automatically, the fastest fix is: delete and recreate the file exactly using a heredoc (no editor, no weird characters).

1) Recreate the file cleanly (copy/paste exactly)

Run:

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset
mkdir -p scripts
rm -f scripts/clean_weiss_csv.mjs

cat > scripts/clean_weiss_csv.mjs <<'EOF'
import * as fs from "node:fs";
import { parse } from "csv-parse/sync";

const IN = "imports/import_weiss_QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster.csv";
const OUT = "imports/import_weiss_QQ-Specials-Premium-Booster.cleaned.csv";

const rarityRegex = /\b(IGP|SP|SSP|SEC|AGR|XR|RRR|RR|SR|R|U|C|PR)\b/i;

const input = fs.readFileSync(IN, "utf8");

const records = parse(input, {
  columns: true,
  skip_empty_lines: true,
  relax_quotes: true,
  relax_column_count: true,
  bom: true,
});

let cleaned = records
  .map((r) => ({
    ...r,
    collector_number_raw: (r.collector_number_raw ?? "").trim(),
    rarity_code: (r.rarity_code ?? "").trim().toUpperCase(),
    is_promo: (r.is_promo ?? "0").toString().trim(),
    card_canonical_name: (r.card_canonical_name ?? "").trim(),
  }))
  .filter((r) => r.card_canonical_name && !/^select table row/i.test(r.card_canonical_name));

cleaned = cleaned.map((r) => {
  if (r.rarity_code) return r;

  const name = r.card_canonical_name || "";
  const num = r.collector_number_raw || "";

  const m1 = name.match(rarityRegex);
  if (m1) { r.rarity_code = m1[1].toUpperCase(); return r; }

  const m2 = num.match(/^[A-Z]{0,6}\d{1,4}([A-Z]{1,4})$/i);
  if (m2) { r.rarity_code = m2[1].toUpperCase(); return r; }

  if (num.toUpperCase() === "PR") {
    r.rarity_code = "PR";
    r.is_promo = "1";
  }

  return r;
});

cleaned = cleaned.map((r) => {
  if (r.rarity_code === "PR" || (r.collector_number_raw || "").toUpperCase() === "PR") r.is_promo = "1";
  return r;
});

// Keep original header order
const headers = Object.keys(records[0] || {});
const escape = (v) => {
  const s = String(v ?? "");
  const t = s.replace(/"/g, '""');
  return /[",\n]/.test(t) ? `"${t}"` : t;
};

const outLines = [
  headers.join(","),
  ...cleaned.map((r) => headers.map((h) => escape(r[h])).join(",")),
];

fs.writeFileSync(OUT, outLines.join("\n"), "utf8");
console.log(` Input rows: ${records.length}`);
console.log(` Cleaned rows: ${cleaned.length}`);
console.log(` Wrote: ${OUT}`);
EOF

Step 5 Check if port 8788 is actually listening

In a second Ubuntu window (or the same one if you stopped the server), run:

bash
ss -lntp | grep 8788 || echo "NOT LISTENING"

What it means

  • If you see a line with :8788 the server is listening.

  • If it says NOT LISTENING wrangler didnt start correctly (even if it didnt look like it errored).

Most common causes + fixes

Cause A: Wrangler is running but on a different port

When you run wrangler pages dev, it sometimes chooses a different port if 8788 is busy.

Fix: Look at the exact URL it prints. Use that.

Cause B: Another process is already using the port

Fix: use a different port:

bash
npx wrangler pages dev .vercel/output/static --compatibility-flags=nodejs_compat --ip 0.0.0.0 --port 8790

Then open:

http://localhost:8790

Cause C: Youre opening the site but Wrangler isnt running anymore

If you see your prompt again in Ubuntu (like romad002@...$) then the server is NOT running.

Below is a copy-paste ready README tailored to the MasteraSet system you built.

MasteraSet Trading Card Collection Tracker

MasteraSet is a web application for tracking and completing trading-card master sets across multiple card games (Weiss Schwarz, Pokmon, etc).
It focuses on true collector ordering not just alphabetic sorting using official set codes, collector numbers, rarity priority, and variants.

This project is deployed locally using Next.js + Cloudflare Pages + D1 (SQLite) via Wrangler.

What MasteraSet Does

For any card set, MasteraSet allows users to:

  • Browse all cards in true set order

  • Filter by:

    • Rarity

    • Language

    • Variant (foil, stamped, etc)

  • Track how many copies they own

  • See missing cards for master-set completion

  • Handle complex numbering schemes used by real TCGs

Why this matters

Most card trackers fail because:

  • They sort alphabetically instead of by collector number

  • They ignore hidden cards, promos, or rarity layers

MasteraSet fixes this by using normalized sorting fields stored in the database.

Supported Sorting Rules

Cards are sorted using this priority:

  1. Set order override (manual fixes)

  2. Numbered vs promo bucket

  3. Numeric value of card number

  4. Prefix (E, PFL, etc)

  5. Suffix (a, b, EX, etc)

  6. Rarity rank

  7. Variant rank

  8. Full collector number

This makes things like:

scss
E38 (C)
E38 (U)
E38 (R)
E38 (RR)
E38 (RRR)
E39
PR-01

sort correctly.

Rarity Priority System

MasteraSet uses rarity ranking so multiple rarities of the same card number appear together:

RankCode
1C
2U
3R
4RR
5RRR
6SR
7SP
8SSP
9IGP
10SEC
11AGR
12XR
99PR (promo if no number)

Promos are always last unless they have a proper collector number.

Tech Stack

  • Next.js (App Router)

  • Cloudflare Pages

  • Cloudflare D1 (SQLite)

  • Wrangler CLI

  • Edge runtime

  • WSL (Ubuntu on Windows)

How to Run Locally

From Windows, open Ubuntu (WSL), then:

bash
cd /mnt/c/Users/Derek/OneDrive/Desktop/Masteraset

Clean and reinstall:

bash
rm -rf node_modules .next .vercel
npm install
npm run pages:build

Run the site:

bash
npx wrangler pages dev .vercel/output/static --compatibility-flags=nodejs_compat --port 8788

Open in Windows browser:

arduino
http://localhost:8788

Database

MasteraSet uses Cloudflare D1 (SQLite).

Tables include:

  • games

  • sets

  • cards

  • printings

  • user_items

The printings table contains all ordering logic:

  • num_value

  • num_prefix

  • num_suffix

  • rarity_rank

  • variant_rank

  • numbered_bucket

  • promo_bucket

This allows perfect sorting regardless of how a TCG formats its numbers.

CSV Import System

Data is imported via CSV files with fields like:

cpp
game_slug
set_code
card_canonical_name
collector_number_raw
rarity_code
variant
language
is_promo

Raw collector numbers like:

nginx
E38
E38a
130/094
PR

are parsed into numeric + prefix + suffix fields during import.

Weiss Schwarz Special Handling

Weiss Schwarz sets support:

  • Multiple rarities per number (C, U, R, RR, RRR, SP, SSP, IGP, SEC, etc)

  • Same card number appearing multiple times

  • Promo cards without numbers

MasteraSet keeps all versions grouped by number and ordered by rarity.

Status

The site is:

  • Built

  • Running locally

  • Connected to a D1 database

  • Successfully rendering sets and cards

  • Supports Weiss Schwarz test data

The next major milestone is:

  • Finalizing CSV imports
